'''Juwan Antonio Howard''' (born February 7, 1973) is an American professional basketball player who plays for the [[Miami Heat]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). The Heat are Howard's eighth NBA team. A one-time [[NBA All-Star Game|All-Star]] and one-time [[All-NBA]] [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]], he began his NBA career as the fifth overall pick in the [[1994 NBA Draft]] by the [[Washington Bullets]]. Before he was drafted, he starred as an [[All-American]] on the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team]]. At Michigan he was part of the [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]] recruiting class of 1991 that reached the finals of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Men's Division I Basketball Championship]] in [[1992 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1992]] and [[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1993]]. Howard won his first NBA championship with Miami in the [[2012 NBA Finals]].

Howard was an All-American [[center (basketball)|center]] and an [[honors student]] at [[Chicago Vocational Career Academy]]. Michigan was able to sign him early over numerous competing offers and then convince others in his recruiting class to join him. The Fab Five, which included [[Chris Webber]], [[Jalen Rose]], [[Jimmy King]] and [[Ray Jackson]], served as regular [[starting lineup|starters]] during their freshman and sophomore years for the [[1991<U+2013>92 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1991<U+2013>92]] and [[1992<U+2013>93 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1992<U+2013>93 Wolverines]]. Howard is the last member of the Fab Five who remains active as a professional basketball player. Although many of the Wolverines' accomplishments from 1992 to 1998 were forfeited due to the [[University of Michigan basketball scandal]], which involved booster payments to players to [[Money laundering|launder money]] from illegal gambling, Howard's [[1994 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1993<U+2013>94 All-American]] season continues to be recognized. 

Howard has played six-and-a-half seasons (1994<U+2013>2001) for the Bullets franchise (renamed the Wizards in 1997), three full seasons (2004<U+2013>2007) for the [[Houston Rockets]], two plus seasons for the Heat and shorter stints for several other teams. During his rookie year with the Bullets, he became the first player to graduate on time with his class after leaving college early to play in the NBA. After one season as an [[NBA All-Rookie Team|All-Rookie]] player and a second as an All-Star and an All-NBA performer, he became the first NBA player to sign a $100&nbsp;million contract. While he continued to be a productive starter, he was never again selected to play in an All-Star Game. Towards the end of his contract, he was traded at the NBA trade deadline twice to make [[salary cap]] room. He was most recently a regular starter during the [[2005<U+2013>06 NBA season]]. In 2010, he signed with the Heat and entered his 17th NBA season, during which he reached the playoffs for the sixth time and made his first career [[2011 NBA Finals|NBA Finals]] appearance. He remained with the Heat the following season and won his first NBA championship during the 2012 NBA Finals. He returned to the Heat for part of the following season. Howard has developed a reputation as a humanitarian for his civic commitment.

==Early life==
Howard's grandmother, Jannie Mae Howard, was the daughter of [[sharecropper]]s from [[Belzoni, Mississippi]]. She had four daughters by her 19th birthday, including Howard's mother Helena. Helena was an employee at a Chicago restaurant when she became pregnant with Juwan. Howard's father, Leroy Watson, had just returned from the Army to a phone company job in Chicago. The two married quickly once they realized Helena was pregnant. For Howard's first week of life, his high school junior mother kept him in a drawer at Jannie Mae's house.<ref name=Albom4>{{cite book|author=Albom|page=4|chapter=}}</ref> Helena, who was 17 years old, did not want to be restricted or burdened raising her child, so Jannie Mae adopted him.<ref name=Hehg/> His biological father, Leroy Watson, Jr., wanted to name him Leroy Watson, III, but his grandmother rejected the suggestion, insisting on Juwan Antonio Howard.<ref name=GmiH>{{cite news|title=Grandma's memory inspires Howard |date=April 5, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=5, sports section|author=Mariotti, Jay}}</ref>  Although his mother visited on occasion as he was growing up, his grandmother raised him,<ref name=Albom4/> along with two cousins.<ref name=CU/> Howard has no siblings and is not close to his biological parents;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/22/sports/sports-of-the-times-the-bullets-may-now-be-loaded.html|title=Sports of The Times; The Bullets May Now Be Loaded|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=November 22, 1994|author=Berkow, Ira|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> his grandmother was the primary influence in his life.<ref name=Albom4/> He moved with her to several low-income [[South Side, Chicago|Chicago South Side]] projects; she kept him out of trouble and away from gangs as he was growing up.<ref name=Albom4/> One of their residences was a three-bedroom apartment on 69th Street on the South Side of Chicago.<ref name=Hehg>{{cite news|title=Howard's effort honors grandma|date=April 7, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Milbert, Neil |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-07/sports/9202010228_1_juwan-howard-michigan-early-period|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> As he blossomed under his grandmother's influence and discipline, he became her "pride and joy".<ref name=Hehg/>

==High school==

Howard attended [[Chicago Vocational Career Academy]], where he went on to play three seasons of varsity basketball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-01-01/sports/1995001153_1_juwan-howard-bullets-atlanta-hawks|title=Bullets' Howard practices positive thinking|accessdate=2013-03-01|date=January 1, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Vocational had an unheated gym and no [[locker room]]s, which required that the team dress for games in a history classroom.<ref name=CU/> Nonetheless, Howard went on to be named a 1991 All-American basketball player by ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' magazine and won [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All American]] honors. He was also chosen for the [[National Honor Society]] and served as Vocational's [[homecoming]] king.<ref name=Hehg/><ref name=GmiH/><ref name=TasiM/><ref name=KHoPA/> During recruiting visits by college coaches such as [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]]' [[Lou Henson]], [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul]]'s [[Joey Meyer (basketball coach)|Joey Meyer]] and [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]]'s [[Steve Fisher]], Jannie Mae Howard did most of the questioning.<ref name=GmiH/>

===Sophomore year===
At the start of his sophomore year in 1988, Howard was 15 years old and already expected to be a coveted [[blue chip (sports)|blue chip]] recruit in 1991.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top players get chance in Shootout|date=December 3, 1988|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=108, sports section}}</ref>  He was regarded as one of the best sophomores in the [[Chicago metropolitan area]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Holiday cheer from tournaments <U+2013> Simeon, King best as most others fail |date=January 2, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=12, sports section}}</ref> He scored 26 points in a [[Chicago Public High School League]] quarterfinal loss against a [[Deon Thomas]]-led [[Simeon Career Academy]] team. Vocational ended the year with a 23&ndash;7 record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brandon free throws lift King|date=March 8, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=119|author=Potash, Mark}}</ref> Howard was a second-team selection and the only sophomore named to the league coaches' 20-man 1988<U+2013>89 All-Public League team.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Public League |date=February 24, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=88, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Brandon top vote getter <U+2013> Thomas next |date=February 24, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=88, sports section}}</ref>

The summer after his sophomore year, the {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|adj=on}} center attended the Nike Academic Betterment and Career Development (ABCD) camp, which was held annually in {{USCity|Princeton|New Jersey}}, during the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/01/25/sonny.vaccaro/|title=End of an era: Vaccaro closes ABCD camp as he eyes hoops academy|accessdate=September 2, 2010|date=January 26, 2007|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Armstrong, Kevin}}</ref> There he was matched against the {{convert|7|ft|4|in|m|2|adj=on}} [[Shawn Bradley]]. At this camp, even though the much-taller Bradley [[block (basketball)|blocked]] his shots several times, Howard established himself as one of the best junior-year [[Basketball terms#B|big men]] in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-13/sports/8902170182_1_henson-won-t-illinois-jamie-brandon|title=- The ultimate redshirt: One of the most unusual stories&nbsp;... |date=July 13, 1989|accessdate=October 6, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Temkin|first=Barry}}</ref>  He was involved in controversy for receiving a second pair of [[Sneaker (footwear)|sneakers]] at the camp because he was suspected of stealing them.<ref name=CHfc/>  Howard denied theft, but he was sent home on the last day of the six-day camp.<ref name=CHfc/>

Howard also participated in the Bill Cronauer camp in {{USCity|Rensselaer|Indiana}}, which more than 100 college coaches attended. According to the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'',  he was ranked as one of the top 10&nbsp;[[underclassmen]] in the country during the camp.<ref name=CHfc>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard fights charge <U+2013> Basketball star fears college coaches, recruiters may back off |date=July 23, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=22, sports section|quote=Howard , a 6<U+2013>8 1/2 junior who is rated among the top 10 underclass prospects in the nation&nbsp;...'I was issued a pair of shoes at the beginning of camp. But they tore. I was issued another pair. Then a counselor gave me another pair. I thought it was a joke. But somebody saw me walk out with a shoebox and thought I had stolen some shoes.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Top stars are waiting|date=July 22, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=105, sports section|quote=...&nbsp;Top 20 all-star game at the B/C camp in Rensselaer, Ind&nbsp;... Juwan Howard , Vocational's 6<U+2013>8 1/2 junior, showed he is a rising star, establishing himself among the top 10 underclassmen in the nation. In the all-star game, he had 18 points and 12 rebounds.}}</ref> Howard attended other camps that summer; his goal was to overcome Thomas, who was the reigning ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' basketball player of the year,<ref name=CTHRD/> as the best big man in the state.<ref name=CHfc/>  By the time he ended his college career in 1994, Howard was drafted a full round ahead of Thomas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1994.html|title=1994 NBA Draft|accessdate=August 8, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>

===Junior year===
As Howard entered his junior year, some sources listed him as the best junior basketball player in Illinois,<ref name=Lpbid>{{cite news|title=Last playoff bids in doubt|date=October 28, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=101, sports section|quote=It's too early to make a formal commitment but Vocational's 6<U+2013>9 Juwan Howard , rated the best junior basketball prospect in the state, is expected to commit to Illinois. Why? Because Illini freshman Deon Thomas is Howard 's idol. They played against each other in high school. Howard still is considering DePaul, however. }}</ref> while others ranked [[Tom Kleinschmidt]] ahead of him.<ref>{{cite news|title=S-T tourney looking a year ahead|date=August 4, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=77, sports section}}</ref> Taylor Bell of the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' noted that Howard was leaning toward playing for either DePaul or for Illinois. Howard was interested in Illinois because Thomas, whom Howard admired, had become a member of the [[1989<U+2013>90 Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball team|1989<U+2013>90 Fighting Illini team]].<ref name=Lpbid/>  By the end of his junior year, league coaches named him to the first-team All-Chicago Public School League.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Public League Selections|date=February 23, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=77, sports section}}</ref>  He was selected to the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' All-Area team as well as the Class-AA All-State team and established himself as the top Chicago-area junior ahead of Kleinschmidt.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Chicago Area Profiles|date=March 2, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=74, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Class-AA All-State Profiles|date=March 16, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=83, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago Area's Top 25 Juniors|date=March 19, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=107, sports section}}</ref>  Howard had a sub-par performance against [[King College Prep High School|King High School]] in the Chicago Public School League semifinals,<ref name=SHcho/>  but the ''Chicago Tribune'' named him to its All-State second team.<ref name=CHcMAS/> Vocational finished the year 24&ndash;7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-03-13/sports/9001210781_1_jamie-brandon-brandon-wasn-t-public-league|title=Brandon, King Streak Past Cvs|accessdate=March 4, 2013|date=March 13, 1990|author=Sullivan, Paul|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>

Howard was also an honors student.<ref name=SHcho/> After his junior year, he was one of 10 Illinois players invited back to the Nike All-American Camp at Princeton. Others invited included Kleinschmidt, [[Donnie Boyce]], [[William Gates (basketball)|William Gates]], [[Billy Taylor (basketball)|Billy Taylor]], [[Rashard Griffith]] and [[Howard Nathan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Penguins hire Johnson, Bowman|date=June 13, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=119, sports section}}</ref>  Although Howard was considered one of the top prospects in the city of Chicago at that time, the player perceived as the best Chicago-area prospect was [[Glenn Robinson]] of [[Gary, Indiana]].<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite news|title=Where the camps will be in action during July|date=July 1, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=25, sports section}}</ref> By this time, Howard had eliminated DePaul from consideration since Deryl Cunningham, another Chicago-area all-star who might have otherwise convinced Howard to stay in Chicago, had transferred to [[Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball|Kansas State]]. He was considering Michigan, [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]], [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]], [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]], [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]], [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] and Illinois.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>  Howard was evaluated as the best senior at the camp; the group of players in attendance included [[Chris Webber]], [[Cherokee Parks]], Robinson and [[Alan Henderson]].<ref name=SHcho/><ref>{{cite news|title=High School Report|date=July 13, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=84, sports section}}</ref>

After being named [[Most Valuable Player]] (MVP) at the prestigious Boston Shootout and acknowledged as the leading participant at the Nike camp, Howard was mentioned as the best prospect in the country. By this time, he had dropped Michigan State and Illinois from his list of possible college destinations and had begun considering [[UNLV Runnin' Rebels basketball|UNLV]] as well.<ref name=SHcho>{{cite news|title=Sought-after Howard considers his options |date=July 15, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Travis, Clyde|page=20, sports section}}</ref> Following his time at the Nike camp, his household was besieged by recruiters. Howard issued the following statement: "Contact my coach. I do not want my grandmother and aunt upset about calls at all times of the day and night. I'm not the only person who lives in this house. I think my wishes should be respected. If not, when it comes time to make my decision, I'll take those things into account."<ref>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard upset by pushy recruiting|date=July 18, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Travis, Clyde|page=111, sports section}}</ref>  Although Howard was the best performer at the camp, talent scout Bob Gibbons felt Webber and Robinson were equally talented prospects.<ref>{{cite news|title=3 top Class of '91 as best in nation <U+2013> CVS' Howard vying for No. 1 rating |date=August 5, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=22, sports section|quote=Gibbons, based in Lenoir, N.C., flew from Charlotte, N.C., to Philadelphia to Washington to Louisville, Ky., to Long Beach, Calif., to Houston to Chicago to Memphis, Tenn., to Las Vegas, Nev., to Lubbock, Texas, to Dallas to Memphis to Charlotte and determined there are three major candidates going into the 1990<U+2013>91 season. And each of them is a 6<U+2013>9 center-forward}}</ref>  Despite Howard's most recently listed college preferences and the fact that the team was under investigation for recruiting violations, Illinois continued pursuing Howard as its number one recruit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Morris Shootout draws Henson's full attention|date=July 23, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Potash, Mark|page=111, sports section}}</ref>  By the end of July 1990, Howard was projected to sign with Michigan.<ref>{{cite news|title=High School Report|date=July 27, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Potash, Mark|page=84, sports section}}</ref>

===Senior year===
During Michigan's in-home visit, Howard's grandmother treated Michigan [[head coach]] Fisher, his assistants [[Mike Boyd (basketball)|Mike Boyd]] and Brian Dutcher, Vocational coach Cook, Vocational assistant coach Donnie Kirskey, Lois Howard (Howard's aunt) and Howard to a [[soul food]] dinner.<ref>{{cite book|author=Albom|page=2|chapter=}}</ref> Dutcher had the responsibility to contact Howard several times a week.<ref name=Albom3>{{cite book|author=Albom|page=3|chapter=}}</ref> Howard grew close to assistant coach Kirskey, often staying at his house and using his car once he got a [[driver's license]].<ref name=Albom5>{{cite book|author=Albom|page=5|chapter=}}</ref> During the summer 1990 30-day visitation period, Dutcher watched Howard practice 28 consecutive days.<ref name=Albom3/> Dutcher developed an understanding of the dynamics of Howard's relationship with his grandmother. While other coaches, such as [[Lute Olsen]], almost ignored her during the recruiting, Dutcher understood that she was the key influence on his life,<ref name=Albom4/> and understood that Kirskey also had sway with Howard. He encouraged Fisher to hire Kirskey for a summer basketball camp that, which became the young athlete's introduction to [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]].<ref name=Albom5/>

Howard was the president of Vocational's Senior Boys' Council.<ref>{{cite book|author=Albom|page=1|chapter=}}</ref> In the final days before his senior season decision regarding his [[college basketball]] team, Howard wavered between [[Arizona State Sun Devils men's basketball|Arizona State]] and Michigan. He also made an official visit to Dayton.<ref name=CHcMAS>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard considers Michigan, Arizona State|date=October 31, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry, Paul Sullivan and Linda Young|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-31/sports/9004020315_1_illinois-state-arizona-state-illini|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Despite the ongoing recruiting scandal, he made an unofficial visit to Illinois, which had recruited four of the five previous Chicago Public School League Illinois Players of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Publics await word on Illini|date=October 29, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=102, sports section}}</ref> At the time of his decision, Howard was considered one of the top five seniors in the country, but unlike many top basketball recruits, he decided not to hold a press conference to announce his choice.<ref>{{cite news|title=CVS star on verge of choice|date=November 1, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-01/sports/9004020352_1_press-conference-cvs-chicago-vocational|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Although the official signing period was set for November 14<U+2013>21, 1990, he selected Michigan on November 2.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan gets CVS' Howard|date=November 2, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry and Steve Nidetz|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-02/sports/9004030441_1_girls-basketball-state-high-school-basketball-boys-action|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Howard's grandmother died of a heart attack a few hours after he announced that he would attend Michigan,<ref name=Hehg/> and he moved in with his high school coach, Richard Cook.<ref name=GmiH/> 

Howard averaged 26.9 points, 8.4 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and 3.4 [[assist (basketball)|assists]] during his senior season,<ref name=Hehg/> and finished in the top 10&nbsp;percent of his academic class.<ref>{{cite news|title=Class of 1991 The dedication|date=June 16, 1991|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-06-16/sports/9102230619_1_state-finals-illinois-state-individual-titles|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> He took Vocational to the Public League semifinals where they lost to [[George Westinghouse College Prep|Westinghouse College Prep]], finishing with a 25&ndash;5 record, despite his 25 points and 12 rebounds.<ref>{{cite news|title=W-house maneuvers past CVS|date=March 10, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=32|author=Potash, Mark}}</ref> He befriended [[Jimmy King]] when they visited Michigan on the same weekend; according to the ''Chicago Tribune'' Fisher Howard influenced King's decision to also enroll there.<ref name=Hehg/><ref>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard already pays Michigan dividend|date=November 11, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry and George Knue|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-11/sports/9004050175_1_juwan-howard-wolverine-prospects|accessdate=September 6, 2010|quote=Thursday, 6-foot-4-inch guard Jimmy King of Plano, Texas, announced he would sign a letter-of-intent with Michigan during the Nov. 14<U+2013>21 early-signing period. King is regarded as one of the top 20 prospects in the nation. A major reason he chose Michigan is the 6<U+2013>9 Howard, who had orally committed to the school a week earlier.}}</ref> According to Clyde Travis of the ''Chicago Sun-Times'', Howard's verbal commitment made up for Fisher's failure to recruit [[Eric Montross]] the prior year,<ref>{{cite news|title=Howard to Michigan |date=November 2, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Travis, Clyde|page=101, sports section|quote=Fisher was desperate to land a player of Howard 's caliber after losing Eric Montross to North Carolina last year and apparently losing 6<U+2013>9 Chris Webber of Birmingham, Mich., the nation's No. 2 prospect this year, to Michigan State. }}</ref> even though Montross' father and grandfather had played for Michigan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dislike Michigan? Count the ways|date=April 5, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |author=Lincicome, Bernie |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-05/sports/9304050210_1_chris-webber-jalen-rose-juwan-howard |accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  With [[Jalen Rose]], Webber, Howard and King&nbsp;<U+2013> along with [[Ray Jackson]], a less-heralded prospect&nbsp;<U+2013> the Michigan recruiting class was considered to be the best in the nation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan adds to riches Wolverines assemble top freshman class|date=April 14, 1991|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-04-14/sports/9102030423_1_michigan-signing-wolverines|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Some regarded the class as among the greatest recruiting classes of all time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan gets top guns 'Great recruiter' Fisher lures 4 of top 10|date=April 28, 1991|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-04-28/sports/9102070824_1_top-point-guards-recruiting-eric-pauley|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan's recruiting class hailed as best|date=March 28, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=94, sports section}}</ref>

As a senior, Howard edged Griffith and [[Kiwane Garris]] for the most votes to the ''Sun-Times''' annual All-Chicago Public School League boys' basketball team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Howard tops All-Public team |date=February 22, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=71, sports section}}</ref>  He was also selected to the All-Area team and was a repeat Class-AA All-State selection.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Chicago Area Boys' Basketball Profiles|date=March 1, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=88, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Boys' Class AA All-State Profiles|date=March 15, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=87, sports section}}</ref>  Howard, Kleinschmidt and Robinson were all selected to the 10-member first team of ''Parade'' magazine's 40-member high school All-America boys' basketball team.<ref name=KHoPA>{{cite news|title=Kleinschmidt, Howard on Parade All-America|date=March 3, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=28, sports section}}</ref>  They were also chosen to play in the McDonald's All-America game.<ref name=TasiM>{{cite news|title=Two area stars in McDonald's|date=March 19, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=79, sports section}}</ref>  West MVP Webber posted 28 points and 12 rebounds in the game; with Howard adding 16 points, the West won 108<U+2013>106.<ref>{{cite news|title=Webber, Howard help West capture McDonald's game|date=April 7, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=30, sports section}}</ref>  Howard also earned the Gatorade Circle of Champions' Illinois Player of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mashburn, Cheaney Top AP All-America|date=March 16, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=75, sports section}}</ref>  Howard's [[ACT test]] score was high enough to make him eligible under [[Proposition 48 (NCAA)|Proposition 48]] academic requirements to play as a freshman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan's Howard eligible|date=April 30, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=81, sports section}}</ref> Only eight of the top 25 Chicago Public School League players achieved a qualifying score on the test.<ref>{{cite news|title=ACT proves disaster for most top recruits <U+2013> Results this season seen as the worst since '84 |date=May 10, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=81, sports section}}</ref>

==College career==

===Freshman year===
[[File:Fab Five original crop.jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]]'s [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]] (left to right) [[Jimmy King]], [[Jalen Rose]], [[Chris Webber]], [[Ray Jackson]] and Howard|alt=five Black males in gold athletic uniforms in the foreground on the sidelines of an athletic court while a few opposing athletes in green wait in the middle of the court.]]
Howard matriculated to the University of Michigan and joined his fellow freshmen for the [[1991<U+2013>92 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1991<U+2013>92 Michigan Wolverines]] in forming a group that became known as the [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]]. He also joined future NBA personalities [[Eric Riley]] and [[Rob Pelinka]].<ref>{{cite news|title='Fab' also applies to this role player|date=April 2, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-02/sports/9304020386_1_lake-forest-michigan-fab|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> As Michigan celebrated [[Midnight Madness (basketball)|Midnight Madness]] on October 15, 1991, there was already talk that at least four of the five freshmen would be starting before the season ended.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago players court fame|author=Bell, Taylor|date=October 15, 1991|page=70, sport section|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref> (The five eventually started in a combined 304 of a possible 350 man-games among them during their first two seasons.)<ref name="MB07-8p13-21"/> Early in his freshman season, Howard started in some games and came off the bench in others for the highly rated Wolverines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-01-18/sports/9201050918_1_illini-program-lou-henson-juwan-howard|title=Illini face Michigan-and the one who got away|date=January 18, 1992|accessdate=October 6, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sullivan, Paul}}</ref> Over time, he won a starting role from Riley.<ref name=HDICT/> In Michigan's first matchup against Illinois, Howard scored 13&nbsp;points and denied Thomas the ball consistently enough to hold him to 8&nbsp;shots. His biggest contribution in the game was getting his hand on a loose ball to force a [[jump ball]] with 16&nbsp;seconds left and Michigan leading by only three points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan holds off Illinois|date=January 19, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sullivan, Paul|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-01-19/sports/9201060339_1_illini-michigan-coach-steve-fisher-lou-henson|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  In the [[Elite Eight]] round of the [[1992 NCAA Men's Division&nbsp;I Basketball Tournament]], Michigan faced a [[Jim Jackson (basketball)|Jimmy Jackson]]-led [[1991<U+2013>92 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State Buckeyes]] team that had beaten them twice during the regular season by double-digit margins.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan's 'Fab Five' vow to have their say|author=Boers, Terry|date=March 29, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=8, sports section}}</ref>  Michigan won the rematch, during which the Fab Five scored all but two of the Wolverines' points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Who'll reign <U+2013> and who'll wane?|author=Hanley, Brian|date=March 30, 1992|page=90, sports section|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref>

The victory gave the 24<U+2013>8 Wolverines a berth in the [[final four|Final Four]], where they found themselves matched against a 29<U+2013>4 [[Bob Huggins]]-coached [[1991<U+2013>92 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team|Cincinnati Bearcats]] team that averaged 83.6&nbsp;[[point (basketball)|points]] per game and had lost to only three teams, two of which had beaten Michigan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fisher out of Michigan spotlight|date=April 4, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Milbert, Neil |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-04/sports/9201310208_1_athletic-director-bo-schembechler-bill-frieder-steve-fisher|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  [[Nick Van Exel]] led Cincinnati in postseason scoring.<ref name=CMcd>{{cite news|title=Cincy-Michigan choice debatable|author=Hanley, Brian|date=April 3, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=93, sports section}}</ref>  Howard, King and Riley shaved their heads for the game.<ref>{{cite news|title='Guilt' keeps Raveling at Southern Cal|date=April 3, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-03/sports/9201310056_1_legendary-high-school-coach-jalen-rose-factor|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Michigan won and earned a rematch with a [[1991-92 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke Blue Devils team]] that had beaten them by three points in overtime in December.<ref name=Hehg/><ref>{{cite news|title=Too young to get this far&nbsp;... Not!|date=April 5, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Lincicome, Bernie |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-05/sports/9201310662_1_college-basketball-blank-slate-duke|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  In the initial contest, Howard had scored only four points.<ref name=Hehg/> Entering the final game, he was averaging 11.2&nbsp;points and 6.3&nbsp;rebounds for the season.<ref name=Hehg/>  The day before the game, Howard had stomach cramps and fever and received fluids to combat dehydration. As a result, he was exempted from mandatory media meetings.<ref name=LHwba>{{cite news|title=Little Hurley wins big award|date=April 7, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Boers, Terry and Brian Hanley|page=85, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Duke fears sprain might sideline Davis|date=April 6, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Boers, Terry and Brian Hanley|page=90, sports section}}</ref>  Howard was part of a rotation with Webber and Riley that guarded the National Player of the Year, [[Christian Laettner]].<ref name=Hehg/>  During Laettner's first six possessions against Howard, Laettner dribbled the basketball off his foot, missed a shot, threw a pass that resulted in a [[turnover (basketball)|turnover]], [[traveling (basketball)|traveled]], threw the ball away and hit the backboard with a shot.<ref name=Hehg/>  Duke scored in its final 12&nbsp;possessions of the championship game, going on a 23<U+2013>6 run to win by a final margin of 71<U+2013>51.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan kids crushed, but Howard sees title in '93.|date=April 7, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Milbert, Neil |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-07/sports/9202010255_1_eastern-michigan-laettner-college-basketball|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Despite his condition, Howard contributed 9&nbsp;points in 29&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=LHwba/> Howard earned a reputation for his quick feet, ability to grasp fundamentals, and excellent moves in the [[low post]], but also for his 1-to-2 assist-to-turnover ratio and a high number of [[foul (basketball)|fouls]].<ref name=Hehg/>

===Sophomore year===
As his sophomore year began, media reports alleged that three Wolverines basketball players were paid $300 each to participate in a charity basketball tournament in mid-1992, during the off-season. The reports further alleged that some others, including Howard, appeared at several summer basketball camps together, which was a possible violation of NCAA rules.<ref>{{cite news|title=3 Ineligible at Michigan <U+2013> Basketball Players Received Money in Charity Tourney |date=September 17, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Rosewater, Amy|page=92, sports section}}</ref>  At the beginning of his [[1992<U+2013>93 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1992<U+2013>93 sophomore season]], Michigan returned its top nine scorers and began the season ranked number one in the country by the [[Associated Press]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U-M At Top Of The Polls|date=November 17, 1992|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Stoda, Greg}}</ref>  Michigan lost its second game of the season in a rematch with {{cbb link|1992|sex=men|team=Duke Blue Devils|school=Duke University|title=Duke}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Tow Take a Tumble <U+2013> Duke, Kansas knock Off Michigan (1), Indiana (2) |date=December 6, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=1, sports section}}</ref> Howard was described as the steadiest player on the team that season by coach Fisher.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fisher praises Howard's play|date=January 12, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Milbert, Neil and Andrew Bagnato|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-01-12/sports/9303161374_1_michigan-indiana-lehigh|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> During the season, Howard purchased a million-dollar disability insurance policy approved by the NCAA under the Exceptional Student Athlete Disability Insurance Program available to student-athletes who are projected to be chosen high in the NBA, [[National Football League]] (NFL), and [[Major League Baseball]] drafts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Super Sophs Are Worth Millions|date=December 18, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=97, sports section}}</ref>

In the semifinals of the [[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] against {{cbb link|1992|sex=men|team=Kentucky Wildcats|school=University of Kentucky|title=Kentucky}}, Howard contributed on offense and held [[Jamal Mashburn]] in check defensively; Mashburn did not make a field goal in the last 12:36 of regulation.<ref name=OAFFPTNF>{{cite news|title=Once Again, Fab Five Prove They're No Fad|date=April 4, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Mariotti, Jay|page=2, sports section|quote=...&nbsp;Juwan Howard , the steady, bullish center from Chicago who did such a terrific defensive job on Jamal Mashburn&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mich. Again <U+2013> N.C., Too <U+2013> Wolverines Fabulous In Overtime|date=April 4, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=1, sports section|quote=Mashburn scored 26 points, but had only nine after halftime and went the last 12:36 of regulation without a field goal.}}</ref> Sportswriter [[Jay Mariotti]] wrote that Howard had done "a terrific defensive job" in guarding Mashburn.<ref name=OAFFPTNF/> The 31<U+2013>4 Wolverines were matched up against the 33<U+2013>4 [[1992<U+2013>93 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina Tar Heels]] in the championship game; both Fisher and North Carolina head coach [[Dean Smith]] were seeking their second national title.<ref>{{cite news|title=Season's end is Finally near Michigan, N. Carolina vie for title|date=April 5, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-05/sports/9304050272_1_lighter-touch-michigan-dean-smith|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  During the championship game Howard picked up his second [[Personal foul (basketball)|personal foul]] with 9&nbsp;minutes 42&nbsp;seconds remaining in the first half and was soon substituted out as the entire team dealt with an accumulation of fouls.<ref>{{cite news|title=Closely called game creates foul mood Carolina wins battle of free throws|date=April 6, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Bagnato, Andrew |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-06/sports/9304060303_1_foul-michigan-bench|accessdate=September 6, 2010|quote=From the beginning, it was clear that the referees were going to call this heavyweight brawl closely. Too closely, Michigan might have thought. By halftime, Wolverines Chris Webber, Juwan Howard and Jimmy King each had two fouls, and Ray Jackson had three&nbsp;... The game shifted when Howard and Webber drew their second fouls in a 64-second span midway through the first half. Howard's second came with 9 minutes 42 seconds until the break; Webber's with 8:38 left. After Webber's foul, Fisher replaced Howard with 7-footer Eric Riley. But Fisher couldn't afford to have both big men on the bench, so Webber had to begin playing cautiously.}}</ref><ref name=Mcft/>  The game would be remembered for a late [[technical foul]] against Webber for attempting to call a [[Time-out (sport)|time out]] when the Wolverines had none left; this led to a Tar Heels victory.<ref name=Mcft>{{cite news|title=Michigan calls fatal timeout|date=April 6, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-06/sports/9304060237_1_tourney-foul-shooting|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Webber deserves a break&nbsp;... and Carolina more credit|date=April 7, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-07/sports/9304070138_1_chris-webber-calling-defenders|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Over the course of the season, Howard averaged 14.6&nbsp;points and 7.4&nbsp;rebounds.<ref>{{cite news|title=College Basketball '93<U+2013>'94 <U+2013> Big Ten Conference|date=November 25, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=133, sports section}}</ref> After the season, Webber and Howard were invited to try out for the United States national basketball team that would compete at the [[1993 Summer Universiade|1993 World University Games]] and [[FIBA Under-21 World Championship|Under-22 World Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Top collegians invited to international tryout|date=April 22, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-22/sports/9304220154_1_invited-shawn-respert-collegians|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Howard did not make the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabasketball.com/mens/worlduniversity/mwug_1993.html|title=Seventeenth World University Games <U+2013> 1993|accessdate=May 22, 2012|publisher=[[USA Basketball]]}}</ref>

===Junior year===
With Webber's departure for the NBA after his sophomore season, the [[1993<U+2013>94 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1993<U+2013>94 Wolverines team]] entered the season ranked fifth in the nation as it opened the season against number&nbsp;13 {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets|school=Georgia Institute of Technology|title=Georgia Tech}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=With No One To Lean On This Season, Michigan's Rose Grows Up|date=November 26, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-11-26/sports/9311260286_1_warriors-webber-chris-webber-michigan|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Since his grandmother had been born on December 25, Howard got a tattoo reading "Jannie Mae" over his heart during Christmas break.<ref name=CU>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007777/1/index.htm|title=Cleaning Up: Juwan Howard, a do-everything forward the Bullets resignedly drafted, is wiping out his NBA opponents|accessdate=March 5, 2013|date=February 26, 1996|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Howard, Johnette}}</ref> During the season, Howard contracted the [[chicken pox]] in January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Game of the Day For Spotty Play <U+2013> Michigan's Howard Chills Listless Illini |date=January 24, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=100, sports section}}</ref>  Michigan had a 21<U+2013>6 (13<U+2013>4 [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]]) record and tied with the [[1993<U+2013>94 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team|Purdue Boilermakers]] for the conference lead with one game remaining.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Ties For Big 10 Lead|date=March 10, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://quicksearch.chipublib.org/cgi-bin/cpl-gr.pl?url=http://proquest.umi.com/pqdweb?did=24244618&sid=2&Fmt=3&clientId=11417&RQT=309&VName=PQD|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Michigan then lost (for the third time in its last four games) to a struggling {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Northwestern Wildcats|school=Northwestern University|title=Northwestern Wildcats}} team,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/13/sports/college-basketball-hard-day-for-high-mighty-arkansas-company-take-falls.html|title=College Basketball; Hard Day for the High and Mighty: Arkansas and Company Take Falls|accessdate=May 19, 2010|date=March 13, 1994|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> and finished second in the Big Ten.<ref name=USRWPMTFHIMR>{{cite news|title=Underdogs Still Running With Pack Maryland, Tulsa Face Heavyweights In Midwest Regional|date=March 25, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Deardorff, Julie|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-25/sports/9403250177_1_michigan-upstart-maryland-regional-semifinal|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> After the season, Howard was selected as a first team All-Big-Ten member along with his teammate Rose, Purdue's Robinson, Michigan State's [[Shawn Respert]], and Indiana's [[Damon Bailey]].<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Big Ten|date=March 15, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=87, sports section}}</ref> In the opening round of the [[1994 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]], Howard helped Michigan to a 78<U+2013>74 overtime victory over {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Pepperdine Waves|school=Pepperdine University|title=Pepperdine}} by scoring 28&nbsp;points and adding 9&nbsp;rebounds before fouling out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Needs OT To Escape Pepperdine|date=March 18, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-18/sports/9403180073_1_damin-lopez-pepperdine-juwan-howard|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> In the second round, Howard posted 34&nbsp;points and 18&nbsp;rebounds to lead the team to an 84<U+2013>79 victory over {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Texas Longhorns|school=University of Texas|title=Texas}}.<ref name=HKMAH3P1RRT>{{cite news|title=Howard Keeps Michigan Alive His 34 Points, 18 Rebounds Repel Texas|date=March 20, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-20/sports/9403200331_1_michigan-texas-juwan-howard|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Michigan faced a [[Joe Smith (basketball)|Joe Smith]]-led {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Maryland Terrapins|school=University of Maryland|title=Maryland}} in the Sweet Sixteen round.<ref name=USRWPMTFHIMR/> Howard scored 24&nbsp;points and had 11&nbsp;rebounds before fouling out with 2:49 remaining in the 78<U+2013>71 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Big Ten Splits <U+2013> Michigan Foils Maryland Bid <U+2013> Arkansas Next|date=March 26, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Gould, Herb|page=104, sports section}}</ref>  Howard earned the regional MVP award with a game-high 30&nbsp;points and 13&nbsp;rebounds in the Elite Eight round, despite collecting two fouls in the first two minutes and losing against the [[1993<U+2013>94 Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball team|Arkansas Razorbacks]], which had [[United States President]] [[Bill Clinton]] in attendance as a vocal supporter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Suffers Shortfall Howard Not Enough, So It's Arkansas|date=March 28, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Deardorff, Julie|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-28/sports/9403280204_1_arkansas-michigan-corliss-big-nasty-williamson|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  On April 18, Howard announced his intention to enter the [[1994 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-04-19/sports/9404190118_1_jannie-mae-howard-webber-and-rose-college-athletics|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Howard, The 'Rock' For Michigan, Enters NBA Draft|date=April 19, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip}}</ref>  The following day, Rose announced he would enter the draft as well.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-04-20/sports/9404200204_1_ncaa-tourney-dugan-fife-travis-conlan|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Michigan's Fav 5 Slips To 2 As Rose Enters NBA Draft|date=April 20, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip}}</ref> Howard was 37 [[credit hour]]s short of University of Michigan degree requirements, but said he intended to keep his promise to his grandmother that he would earn his diploma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/19/sports/sports-people-college-basketball-howard-of-michigan-to-enter-nba-draft.html|title=Sports People: College Basketball; Howard of Michigan To Enter N.B.A. Draft|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=April 19, 1994|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

Howard left Michigan after being named an Associated Press third team [[1994 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] during his junior year, and was taken by the [[Washington Wizards|Washington Bullets]] fifth overall in the 1994 NBA Draft.<ref name=JHBR>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01.html|title=Juwan Howard|accessdate=May 18, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard was represented by [[David Falk]].<ref name=HHOARBHAN>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-09-28/sports/9409280024_1_bulls-vinson-smith-bears|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Howard Hangs Out As Rumors Bounce Him Around NBA|date=September 28, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry}}</ref> Although the Fab Five's games in the Final Four have since been forfeited,<ref name="MB07-8p8">{{cite book |title=2007<U+2013>08 Men's Basketball Media Guide |publisher=University of Michigan |page=8 |year=2007}}</ref> Howard was not among the players, which included [[Robert Traylor]], Webber, Rose, [[Maurice Taylor]], and [[Louis Bullock]], called before a [[grand jury]] to testify<ref name="FUaatiMc">{{cite news |title=Former U-M assistant testifies in Martin case: Also, prosecutors issue two indictments of Martin's associates  |date=October 19, 2000 |publisher=Michigan Live LLC |work=[[Ann Arbor News]] |author=Larcom,Geoff}}</ref> in the [[University of Michigan basketball scandal]]. He was not implicated in the scandal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Text of the indictment  |date=March 22, 2002 |publisher=Michigan Live LLC |work=[[Ann Arbor News]]}}</ref> Although the NCAA sanctioned Michigan Wolverines men's basketball by forfeiting many of its records and accomplishments from 1992 to 1998, Howard's status as a 1993<U+2013>94 All-American remained intact.<ref name="MB07-8p13-21">{{cite book |title=2007<U+2013>08 Men's Basketball Media Guide |publisher=University of Michigan |pages=13<U+2013>21 |year=2007}}</ref>

==Professional career==

===Scouting report===
In college, Howard was regarded as one of the best defensive big men in the country.<ref name=HDICT>{{cite news|title=Howard's Dream Is Coming True|date=April 5, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bickley, Dan|page=99}}</ref> According to Mariotti, he was also regarded as a "rock-solid" power forward who provided rebounds and defense, in contrast to his flamboyant teammate Webber.<ref>{{cite news|title=Should Muscle-less Bulls Eye Howard or Webber?|date=November 11, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Mariotti, Jay|page=143|quote=If Howard is considered a rock-solid, rebounds-and-defense power forward, Webber is the total showtime package, the transcendent franchise player.}}</ref> Fisher referred to Howard as his "[[Rock of Gibraltar]]".<ref name=HKMAH3P1RRT/> His consistency was described by ''Chicago Tribune'' journalist Skip Myslenski as Michigan's "ballast, steadying them on those many occasions when they wavered. And their savior, rescuing them from their many follies".<ref name=HKMAH3P1RRT/>

After the 1994 Draft, NBA analyst [[Doug Collins (basketball)|Doug Collins]] described Howard as a player who can "play with his back to the basket and can shoot from about 16 feet outside" and who "plays with a lot of energy and emotion".<ref name=CTHRD>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-06-30/sports/9406300233_1_national-basketball-association-draft-dallas-guard-tony-dumas|title=Chicagoans Thomas, Howard Realize Dreams|accessdate=September 12, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=June 30, 1994|author=Sakamoto, Bob}}</ref> The Bullets' [[general manager]], [[John Nash (basketball)|John Nash]], who was disappointed that [[Jason Kidd]] was no longer available at the fifth pick of the draft,<ref name=CU/> told Jerry Bembry of ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' that Howard was "as fundamentally sound as any player in the draft" and that he "has a discipline about his game and uses a high level of skill and technique". Bembry said, "Not only can Howard post up, he passes effectively and is able to hit a jumper up to 17 feet," adding that he "also is an excellent position defender".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-06-30/sports/1994181190_1_juwan-howard-bullets-shawn-kemp|title=Bullets say Howard is good deal|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=June 30, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref>  Later Bembry noted that he was a power forward who was able to play center, adding that at Michigan he was "most effective playing with his back to the basket" but could also pass effectively and hit medium-range [[Jump shot (basketball)|jumpers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-07-06/sports/1994187031_1_howard-jim-mcilvaine-bullets|title=Howard's attitude wins over Bullets|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=July 6, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> The Bullets' head coach, [[Jim Lynam]], described Howard as a "complete player" and noted that "he can defend you and he can score over you".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-07-01/sports/1994182025_1_bullets-gheorghe-muresan-calbert|title=Bullets give defense 1<U+2013>2 punch|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=July 1, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Nash said that "the things that impressed me most about him were his character, his intelligence and his insight. He's a leader type."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-06-30/sports/1994181182_1_jim-lynam-juwan-howard-john-nash|title=Underclass names change, but NBA teams remain predictably ecstatic|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=June 30, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Jackman, Phil}}</ref>

When he first became a [[free agent]] in 1996, Howard was described as versatile enough to play all three front-line positions ([[small forward]], power forward and center), and [[Michael Jordan]] praised his "game, work ethic and character".<ref>{{cite news|title=The key to Bulls' future could be Juwan Howard |date=June 25, 1996|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Jackson, John|page=96}}</ref>  As a Dallas player in 2000<U+2013>01, he was still regarded as a versatile offensive player who could "take advantage of smaller defenders in the paint and then stretch his bigger defenders outside" in addition to being a solid rebounder.<ref name=PBMHHSoS>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/14/sports/pro-basketball-mavericks-howard-has-smile-of-success.html|title=Pro Basketball; Mavericks' Howard Has Smile of Success|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=March 14, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Robbins, Liz}}</ref>  By 2001, Lacy J. Banks from the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' regarded him as a high-priced, under-achieving player,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Man Who Drafted Jordan might finally get his due|date=November 18, 2001|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J.|page=118}}</ref>  but in 2002, Banks described him as a solid veteran at the four (power forward position).<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunleavy heads talented group of small forwards|date=June 23, 2002|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J.|page=114}}</ref> In the NBA, Howard developed a respected inside post-up game and a reputation as a veteran leader, according to [[Kiki Vandeweghe]], the general manager of the [[Denver Nuggets]], Howard's team in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Van Exel reserves best for playoffs|date=May 18, 2003|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J.|page=105, sports section}}</ref>

When he signed with the Heat in 2010, Howard was lauded for his ability to play the power forward and center positions and for his professionalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/roster/heat_signs_juwan_howard_2010_07_20.html|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=September 12, 2012|date=July 20, 2010|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> Howard also added frontcourt toughness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/writers/ian_thomsen/07/21/east.contenders/|title=Sneak peek at East contenders|accessdate=September 12, 2012|date=July 21, 2010|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Thomsen, Ian}}</ref> As an elder statesman with the Heat, he was regarded as a future NBA coach or general manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/27/2868195/miami-heats-juwan-howard-finally.html|title=Miami Heat's Juwan Howard finally captures a title for the Michigan Fab Five|accessdate=September 12, 2012|date=June 27, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Neal, David J.}}</ref>

===Washington Bullets era (1994<U+2013>96)===
Entering the {{nbay|1994|app=season}}, the NBA players and owners had not yet agreed on the terms of a new [[collective bargaining agreement]], and Howard was unsigned two weeks before training camp began. He continued to train in Chicago in late September amidst rumors that his draft rights could be traded to another team.<ref name=HHOARBHAN/>  While holding out, he was rumored to be part of a trade package with the [[1994<U+2013>95 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago Bulls]] that included [[Calbert Cheaney]] and a first-round draft choice in exchange for [[Scottie Pippen]].<ref name=EGHORTNS/><ref>{{cite news|title=Pippen Talk Heats Up in Miami Again|date=August 25, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=94, sports section}}</ref> Another rumor had Howard being packaged with [[Rex Chapman]] and [[Don MacLean (basketball)|Don MacLean]] for Pippen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bullets Pursuing Pippen, But Bulls Aren't Biting|date=July 23, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=93, sports section}}</ref>  On November 9, eleventh overall 1994 NBA Draft selection [[Carlos Rogers (basketball)|Carlos Rogers]] signed an NBA contract, making Howard the last first-round selection without a contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=9-Year Deal For Warriors' Rogers Howard Is Only First-Round Pick Who Hasn't Signed|date=November 9, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://quicksearch.chipublib.org/cgi-bin/cpl-gr.pl?url=http://proquest.umi.com/pqdweb?did=24098153&sid=2&Fmt=3&clientId=11417&RQT=309&VName=PQD|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> He missed most of the first month of the season and resided at an [[O'Hare Airport]] hotel while protracted talks continued.<ref name=EGHORTNS>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-02-15/sports/9502150107_1_juwan-howard-bulls-general-manager-jerry-bullets-coach-jim-lynam|title=Ex-CVS Great Howard On Rise To NBA Stardom|accessdate=September 6, 2010|date=February 15, 1995|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref> Howard's agent [[David Falk]] said that one of the main problems was that the Bullets wanted Howard to sign for a lower average salary than number six selection [[Sharone Wright]].<ref name=CU/> The Bullets stuck to a 10-year, $30&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|30|1994|r=1}}}}&nbsp;million in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) offer.<ref>{{cite news|title=English Breathes Sigh of Relief|date=October 30, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Jackson, John|page=21, sports section}}</ref> On November 17,<ref name=WGW>{{cite news|title=Webber Gets Wish <U+2013> Sent to Bullets For Gugliotta, 3 No. 1 Picks |date=November 18, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Heisler, Mark|page=146, sports section}}</ref> Howard signed what was believed to be a 12-year, $37.5&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|37.5|1994|r=1}}}}&nbsp;million) contract.<ref name=EGHORTNS/> Howard's contract, which ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' later said was an 11-year $36&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|36|1994|r=1}}}}&nbsp;million) deal, had an [[escape clause]].<ref name=CU/> Once he signed, he was reunited with Michigan teammate Webber as a member of the Bullets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-01-03/features/9501030015_1_juwan-howard-skyhook-michigan|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Bros In The Pros Ex-College Teammates Take On NBA Together|date=January 3, 1995|author=Hanrahan, Brendan |work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  Webber, who had also sat out training camp and the first eight games of the season,<ref name=WHBB>{{cite news|title=Webber, Howard Bolster Bullets|date=November 20, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J. |page=13, sports section}}</ref> was traded from the {{NBA Year|1994|team=Golden State Warriors|title=Golden State Warriors}} to the Bullets on November 18 for [[Tom Gugliotta]] and three first-round draft choices.<ref name=WGW/>

After Webber joined the Bullets, many thought that the two former Fab Five members would bring success to the team, coached by Lynam. The Washington front line was expected to include Webber, Howard, and [[Kevin Duckworth]] and to have [[Gheorghe Mure<U+0219>an]], a {{convert|7|ft|7|in|cm|adj=on}} [[Romania]]n center, coming off the bench.<ref name=WHBB/>  Chapman, MacLean, Cheaney, [[Mitchell Butler]] and [[Scott Skiles]] were expected to provide solid perimeter play.<ref name=WHBB/> Experts projected the Bullets as contenders for the Eastern Conference title.<ref name=WHBB/> The Howard/Webber Bullets debut against the [[Boston Celtics]] established new Bullets [[Nielsen ratings|television ratings]] records for the [[Home Team Sports]] network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-11-25/sports/1994329009_1_tomorrow-night-juwan-howard-game|title=There's much TV to feast upon|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 25, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Kent, Milton}}</ref> However, the early season trade left the team in a state of confusion due to lack of familiarity, which resulted in communication difficulties on the court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-11-29/sports/1994333156_1_larry-stewart-bullets-juwan-howard|title=Unfamiliarity leaves Bullets lost, for now|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 29, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Tanton, Bill}}</ref> Howard eventually moved into the starting lineup.<ref name=EGHORTNS/> As a power forward, Howard posted impressive numbers after he became a regular starter.<ref name=EGHORTNS/>  Howard participated in the February 11, 1995, [[1995 NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Game]] weekend events as a member of the [[Rising Stars Challenge|Rookie Challenge]].<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Star Facts|date=February 11, 1995|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=94, sports section}}</ref>  He earned second team All-Rookie honors at the end of the season.<ref name=JHBR/> That month, he became the second Bullet (since the award's inception in 1981) and first since [[Jeff Ruland]] in January 1982 to be named NBA Rookie of the Month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wizards-insider/wp/2013/01/03/bradley-beal-wins-eastern-conference-rookie-of-the-month/|title=Bradley Beal wins Eastern Conference rookie of the month|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 26, 1995|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Lee, Micheal}}</ref> During the month he averaged 20.1 points, 8 rebounds and 1.2 blocks in 14 games, including his first two 30-point games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-03-02/sports/1995061131_1_howard-juwan-grant-hill|title=Howard top player in February|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=March 2, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> The following month Howard suffered an ankle injury, missing a total of 10 games (all of which were Bullets losses).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-04-14/sports/1995104072_1_bullets-13th-straight-game-chris-webber|title=Bullets drop 13th straight game|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=April 14, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Over the course of the season, he averaged 17.0&nbsp;points per game and posted 17&nbsp;[[Double (basketball)#Double-double|double-double]]s in 65&nbsp;games played (52&nbsp;starts).<ref name=JHBR/><ref name=JH95GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1995/|title=Juwan Howard 1994<U+2013>95 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  He totalled 30&nbsp;points or more on three separate occasions.<ref name=JH95GL/>  The members of the team combined to miss a total of 317&nbsp;games due to injury,<ref name=CBFEOP/> and the team finished the season with a 21<U+2013>61&nbsp;record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1995.html|title=1994<U+2013>95 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>

Howard became the first NBA athlete who entered the draft early and graduated with his academic class,<ref name=JHNBABIO>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/bio.html |title=Players: Juwan Howard (Bio) |accessdate=August 20, 2008 |publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> thus fulfilling a promise he had made to his grandmother on the last day he saw her alive.<ref name=FHSCBD/><ref name=TADHKHPTHG/> He told [[Mitch Albom]] that when he made it to the NBA, he realized how much leisure time the multimillionaire players had and decided to do something productive instead of find ways to spend his new riches. "I knew if I kept pushing it off, I'd never get it done," he said. He completed his final 32 course hours by taking summer classes in 1994 during the NBA off-season. He took correspondence classes and [[independent study]] courses during the following season, studying on road trips and mailing in his papers from the nearest post office. In the end, he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in radio-television communication (with a minor in business) at Michigan. He told Albom that earning his degree made him a better example when speaking about staying in school.<ref name=TADHKHPTHG>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rOgyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wgcGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6140,5912218&dq=juwan+howard+graduation&hl=en|title=To A Degree, Howard Keeps His Promise To His Grandmother|author=Albom, Mitch|work=[[The Free Lance-Star]]|accessdate=September 14, 2010|date=April 29, 1995}}</ref>  Although Howard had spent the prior year playing in the NBA, he returned to campus to partake in graduation ceremonies with his classmates.<ref name=FHSCBD>{{cite web|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/19558776.html?dids=19558776:19558776&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+30%2C+1995&author=Rachel+Alexander&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=For+Howard%2C+Success+Comes+By+Degree%3B+Bullets+Rookie%27s+Hard+Work+Leads+to+Michigan+Graduation&pqatl=google|title=For Howard, Success Comes By Degree; Bullets Rookie's Hard Work Leads to Michigan Graduation|accessdate=September 14, 2010|date=April 30, 1995|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Alexander, Rachel|page=DO1}}</ref>   During the graduation, keynote speaker [[Marian Wright Edelman]] paid special recognition to Howard and Fab Five teammates King and Jackson, who graduated together, and noted that Howard's graduation made him a role model for children.<ref>{{cite news|title='95 Seniors Bid Bittersweet Goodbye To Blue|author=Klein, Stephanie Jo|work=[[Michigan Daily]]|date=May 3, 1995}}</ref>

In the off-season, the {{NBA Year|1995|team=Washington Bullets|title=Bullets}} traded Chapman, MacLean and Duckworth,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/chapmre01.html|title=Rex Chapman|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/macledo01.html|title=Don MacLean|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/duckwke01.html|title=Kevin Duckworth|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> and drafted [[Rasheed Wallace]] in the [[1995 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/w/wallara01.html|title=Rasheed Wallace|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> In the preseason, the Bullets played the [[Detroit Pistons]] in an October game at the University of Michigan's [[Crisler Arena]], marking a homecoming for Howard. Webber was sidelined with a shoulder injury and missed the homecoming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-10-26/sports/1995299094_1_juwan-howard-bullets-homecoming|title=At Michigan, Howard savors a fabulous homecoming Bullets forward remains a big man on campus|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 26, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Prior to the [[1995<U+2013>96 NBA season|1995<U+2013>96 season]], the Bullets were expected to be a contender with Webber, Howard, Muresan, [[Mark Price]], and [[Robert Pack]]. However, Webber, Price and Pack missed almost the entire year (65, 75 and 51&nbsp;games respectively) because of injuries.<ref name=CBFEOP>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/22093080.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Apr+21%2C+1996&author=J.A.+Adande&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=D.01&desc=Caps%2C+Bullets+Feel+Each+Other%27s+Pain%3B+Injuries+Story+of+Their+Seasons|title=Caps, Bullets Feel Each Other's Pain; Injuries Story of Their Seasons|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 21, 1996|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=D01}}</ref>  In February, the [[New York Knicks]] made two trades that put them in position to bid on Howard in the 1996 free agent market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/20/sports/basketball-howard-hopes-knicks-wish.html|title=Basketball;Howard Hopes, Knicks Wish|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 20, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Since Falk was the agent for both [[Patrick Ewing]] and Howard, sportswriter [[Dave Anderson (sportswriter)|Dave Anderson]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' felt the Knicks would have a good chance at Howard in July when the free agent market began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/23/sports/sports-of-the-times-will-ewing-help-knicks-get-howard.html|title=Sports Of The Times;Will Ewing Help Knicks Get Howard?|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 23, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Anderson, Dave}}</ref>

Howard earned his only career [[NBA All-Star Game]] selection for the February 11, [[1996 NBA All-Star Game|1996 game]].<ref name=JHBR/> A ''Sports Illustrated'' story showed examples of him dominating games at will during that season.<ref name=CU/> Howard also made news that season for his theatrics after being ejected from a February 27 game against the [[New Orleans Hornets|Charlotte Hornets]]. He kicked a water cooler across the court and was fined $5,000 for making an obscene gesture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/28/sports/sports-people-pro-basketball-a-costly-gesture-by-bullets-howard.html|title=Sporst People: Pro Basketball; A Costly Gesture by Bullets' Howard|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=February 28, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  He concluded the season by scoring at least 20&nbsp;points in his last 16&nbsp;games.<ref name=JH96GL/>  Howard became just the second player in Washington franchise history, after [[Bernard King]], to post back-to-back 40-point games (against [[1995<U+2013>96 Boston Celtics season|Boston]] on April 17, 1996, with 40, and at [[1995<U+2013>96 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto]] on April 19, 1996, with 42).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores96/96108/96108391.htm|title=Celtics vs. Bullets|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 17, 1996|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores96/96110/96110397.htm|title=Bullets vs. Raptors|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 19, 1996|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>  The 42&nbsp;points proved to be his career high.<ref name=JHNBASTATS>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/career_stats.html|title=Players: Juwan Howard (Career Stats and Totals) |accessdate=May 20, 2010 |publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> His strong finish earned him an NBA Player of the Month award for April.<ref name=JHNBABIO/> In spite of the injuries to key teammates, 1995<U+2013>96 was Howard's best season, statistically. During the season, he finished 3rd in the NBA in minutes played, 6th in points scored and 10th in points per game (22.1).<ref name=JHBR/> He was the Bullets' leading scorer.<ref name=BaHdHwfa>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-08-09/sports/1996222088_1_juwan-howard-miami-heat-arbitration|title=Bullets await Howard decision Heat will force arbitration: no date set for hearing|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=August 9, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Goldstein, Alan}}</ref> Over the course of the season, he accumulated 22&nbsp;double-doubles in 81&nbsp;games, including 6 in his last 8&nbsp;games.<ref name=JH96GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1996/|title=Juwan Howard 1995<U+2013>96 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  At the end of the season, he was named to the [[All-NBA]] team.<ref name=JHBR/>  In addition to his two 40-point performances, he posted 3 additional 30-point performances and scored at least 20&nbsp;points in 56 of 81&nbsp;games.<ref name=JH96GL/>  Averaging 22.1&nbsp;points, 8.1&nbsp;rebounds and 4.4&nbsp;assists,<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  he helped the Bullets record 39&nbsp;victories.<ref name=JH96GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1996.html|title=1995<U+2013>96 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> This was not enough for the Bullets to make the playoffs during their ninth consecutive losing season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/22093004.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Apr+21%2C+1996&author=Richard+Justice&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=D.10&desc=Howard+to+Bullets%3A+%60It%27s+My+Turn%27|title=Howard to Bullets: 'It's My Turn'|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 21, 1996|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Justice, Richard|page=D10}}</ref>

After averaging 17&nbsp;points per game as a rookie and more than 22&nbsp;per game in his second season, Howard became a free agent when the Bullets made some salary cap transactions. The Bullets offered Howard an $89&nbsp;million contract, but the [[Miami Heat]] outbid them with a seven-year deal estimated to be worth  $98 to $101&nbsp;million. However, according the NBA league office, the Heat miscalculated their available salary under the [[salary cap]] by excluding performance bonuses for [[Tim Hardaway]] and [[P. J. Brown]] and failing to account for the impact of renegotiating [[Alonzo Mourning]]'s contract before coming to terms with Howard.<ref name=NRHD/> The league rejected the contract on July 31 because Howard's $9&nbsp;million for the [[1996<U+2013>97 NBA season|1996<U+2013>97 season]] placed the Heat over the cap.<ref name=NRHD>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/01/sports/nba-rejects-howard-deal.html|title=N.B.A. Rejects Howard Deal|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 1, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=HATRtB>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/05/sports/howard-attempting-to-return-to-bullets.html|title=Howard Attempting To Return to Bullets|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 5, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Howard then re-signed with the Bullets on August 5. He became the first player in NBA history to sign a contract worth more than $100&nbsp;million;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://athletes-celebrities.tseworld.com/sports/basketball/juwan-howard.php|title=Juwan Howard|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Premiere Global Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truthaboutit.net/2010/04/cardboard-bullets-juwan-howard-the-original-100-million-man.html|title=Cardboard Bullets: Juwan Howard, the original $100 million man|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=April 28, 2010|author=Weidie, Kyle|publisher=Truth About It}}</ref> his seven-year contract was worth $105&nbsp;million. The league ruled on August 5 that the Bullets could re-sign Howard after having renounced his rights on July 15 to free up cap room to sign [[Tracy Murray]] and [[Lorenzo Williams (basketball)|Lorenzo Williams]] if they forfeited their [[1997 NBA Draft]] first-round selection rights.<ref name=H2D2T2M>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/06/sports/howard-2-deals-2-teams-200-million.html|title=Howard: 2 Deals, 2 Teams, $200 Million|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 6, 1996|author=Brown, Clifton|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The Bullets were not limited by the cap because they were re-signing their own player.<ref name=HATRtB/> The Heat pursued legal remedy in Florida state courts, seeking acknowledgment of the prior validity and superiority of their earlier contract.<ref name=H2D2T2M/>  Although an arbitration case involving the two contracts that Howard had signed appeared likely, [[ESPN]] reported that the Heat dropped their legal pursuit of Howard.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/07/sports/where-will-howard-play-next-season.html|title=Where Will Howard Play Next Season?|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 7, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The league moved for federal jurisdiction although the case remained on the docket for [[New York University]] law professor Daniel Collins to serve as arbitrator on three issues: "1.) Did the Heat circumvent the cap in first signing Mourning?; 2.) Did the Heat miscalculate bonus money for forward P. J. Brown and guard Tim Hardaway that was not counted correctly against the cap.?; 3.) Did the Heat add an illegal performance clause to Brown's contract?." Meanwhile the Heat's contract was protected by a [[temporary injunction]] in Florida state court, which forbade any newer contract by Howard from abrogating his Miami contract.<ref name=BaHdHwfa/> The Heat eventually dropped their case but the team, especially head coach [[Pat Riley]], continued to vehemently claim that their case of wrongdoing in the form of erroneous rulings by the league had been very solid.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/13/sports/an-angry-pat-riley-insists-the-heat-broke-no-salary-cap-rules.html|title=An Angry Pat Riley Insists the Heat Broke No Salary Cap Rules|accessdate=May 1, 2013|date=August 13, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Brown, Clifton}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/15/sports/hoop-it-up-free-agents-costly-errors.html|title=Hoop It Up: Free Agents, Costly Errors|accessdate=May 1, 2013|date=August 15, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Brown, Clifton}}</ref> If the Heat had pursued arbitration and had been found guilty of violating the salary cap, the team could have been fined $5&nbsp;million and Heat coach Riley could have been suspended for the season. By dropping their actions, the Heat avoided any possible penalties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/11/sports/howard-will-remain-a-bullet-after-all.html|title=Howard Will Remain a Bullet, After All|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 11, 1996|author=Brown, Clifton|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  In addition to signing free agents Murray and Williams, the Bullets traded for [[Rod Strickland]] and [[Harvey Grant]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/10/sports/bullets-open-up-their-gifts-and-run.html|title=Bullets Open Up Their Gifts and Run|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=November 10, 1996|author=Brown, Clifton|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

===Washington Wizards era (1996<U+2013>2001)===

As a statement against gun violence, Bullets owner [[Abe Pollin]] sought to change the franchise's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dcsportsbog/2010/02/why_abe_pollin_went_from_bulle.html|title=Why Abe Pollin went from Bullets to Wizards|accessdate=July 12, 2012|date=February 2, 2010|author=Steinberg, Dan|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> The Bullets became the {{NBA Year|1996|team=Washington Wizards|title=Washington Wizards}} after asking fans to vote on the name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/23/sports/sports-people-pro-basketball-bullets-will-be-wizards.html|title=Sports People: Pro Basketball;Bullets Will Be Wizards|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=February 23, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Although before the [[1996<U+2013>97 NBA season]] the Bullets/Wizards were expected to make the playoffs with Webber, Howard, and Strickland, there were rumors that Webber had difficulty adjusting to being a less important part of the offensive game plan in the presence of All-Star Howard.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-10-31/sports/1996305024_1_chris-webber-webber-award-juwan-howard|title=Injuries a sore spot for Webber Limited past 2 years, forward eager to reap benefits of hard work|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 31, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry }}</ref> Howard was plagued with [[shin splints]], causing him to miss several preseason games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-10-20/sports/1996294078_1_bullets-juwan-howard-murray|title=Bullets' Murray takes step up on home turf Ex-UCLA star scores 22 to beat 76ers, 119<U+2013>104|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 20, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry }}</ref> On November 11, 1996, Howard failed a sobriety test when he was caught [[speeding]] and was charged with [[driving while intoxicated]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-11-12/sports/1996317060_1_howard-foundation-juwan-howard-bullets|title=Howard apologizes after DWI arrest Bullets All-Star due in court Dec. 6|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 12, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry }}</ref> The following month he pled not guilty and committed to enter an alcohol rehabilitation and education program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1996/Howard-Pleads-Not-Guilty-Enters-Alcohol-Education-Program/id-170f198c08cee08b4b1f7bf70617ebee|title=Howard Pleads Not Guilty, Enters Alcohol Education Program|accessdate=2013-03-12|date=December 3, 1996|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> After Lynam coached the Bullets to a 22<U+2013>24 record, he was fired and the Bullets hired [[Bernie Bickerstaff]], who posted a 22<U+2013>13 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1997.html|title=1996<U+2013>97 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Over the course of the 1996<U+2013>97 season, Howard accumulated 24&nbsp;double&nbsp;doubles in 82&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH97GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1997/|title=Juwan Howard 1996<U+2013>97 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 19.1&nbsp;points and 8.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> Although Howard averaged over 19&nbsp;points per game and played all 82&nbsp;games,<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> he only scored 30 or more points twice during the regular season.<ref name=JH97GL/>   The team finished its regular season with a 44<U+2013>38 record but was swept in three games in the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] first round by the [[1996<U+2013>97 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago Bulls]], who went on to win their second consecutive NBA championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1997.html|title=1996<U+2013>97 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> The [[1997 NBA Playoffs]] were Howard's only NBA playoff appearance in his six-plus seasons with the Washington franchise, and he averaged 18.7&nbsp;points and 6&nbsp;rebounds while playing 43&nbsp;minutes per game.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> The playoff appearance marked the franchise's first playoff appearance since the [[1988 NBA Playoffs]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1997-04-26/sports/7901011233_1_chicago-bulls-bullets-webber|title=Bulls Strike First, 98<U+2013>86: Jordan, Playoff Savvy Get 1<U+2013>0 Lead On Bullets As Webber Struggles|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=April 26, 1997|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref>

The {{NBA Year|1997|team=Washington Wizards|title=Wizards}} relocated from the [[US Airways Arena]] to the [[MCI Center]] for the  [[1997<U+2013>98 NBA season|1997<U+2013>98 season]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/30/sports/nba-last-night-wizards-farewell-party-is-ruined-by-the-bulls.html|title=N.B.A: Last Night; Wizards' Farewell Party Is Ruined by the Bulls|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=November 30, 1997|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> during which Howard totaled 11&nbsp;double-doubles in 64&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH98GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1998/|title=Juwan Howard 1997<U+2013>98 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.5&nbsp;points and 8.0&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  He scored between 20 and 29 points 31 times that season but failed to score 30&nbsp;points in any game.<ref name=JH98GL/>  Howard injured his ankle and was unable to play between February 5 and March 17.<ref name=JH98GL/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-02-22/sports/9802220216_1_bulls-washington-coach-bernie-bickerstaff-webber-and-howard|title=Bulls 94, Wizards 88: The Wiz End Up As A Fizz: Clinton On Hand For Latest Defeat|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=February 22, 1998|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry}}</ref>  During Bickerstaff's only full season as the Washington coach, the team posted a 42<U+2013>40 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/1998.html|title=1997<U+2013>98 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>

On April 6, 1998, Melissa Reed filed a sexual assault complaint against Howard and Webber after a party at Howard's house. Lawyers for both offered different accounts.  Howard's lawyer said that Reed had initiated an unspecified consensual sex act with one of the men, but Reed, who could not afford a lawyer,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1998/Wizards-Howard-Wins-Lawsuit/id-b3c0158a21aa80d7623631219fd0188b|title=Wizards' Howard Wins Lawsuit|accessdate=July 12, 2012|date=November 12, 1998|agency=Associated Press|author=Zuckerbrod, Nancy}}</ref> claimed to have entered a room with Webber before being struck and restrained prior to being sexually assaulted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/basketball/nba/news/1998/09/18/howard_suit/|title=Wizards' Howard moves ahead with lawsuit against accuser|accessdate=July 12, 2012|date=September 18, 1998|work=[[CNN Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> Neither Howard nor Webber testified in the case, and although the accuser and approximately 40 of the party attendees appeared before a grand jury, the [[Montgomery County, Maryland|Montgomery County]] [[State's Attorney]] announced that prosecution was not warranted and closed the case in May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/05/22/sports/nba-last-night-webber-and-howard-case-closed.html|title=N.B.A.: Last Night; Webber And Howard Case Closed|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=May 22, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> This came just after the Wizards' general manager [[Wes Unseld]] separated Webber and Howard on May 15 by trading Webber to the [[Sacramento Kings]], receiving [[Mitch Richmond]] and [[Otis Thorpe]] in exchange.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/05/15/sports/nba-webber-traded-to-sacramento.html|title=N.B.A.; Webber Traded to Sacramento|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 15, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  In June, Howard filed suit against Reed, seeking compensation for emotional distress for damage to his reputation and image.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/06/27/sports/plus-in-the-news-howard-sues-his-accuser.html|title=Ps: In The News; Howard Sues His Accuser|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=June 27, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  The accuser was absent during the proceeding and failed to respond to the lawsuit for [[defamation]]. In November, Howard was awarded the $1 in [[compensatory damages]] that he sought to clear his name and $100,000 in [[punitive damages]] plus legal costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/13/sports/nba-roundup-wizards-court-awards-100000-to-howard.html|title=N.B.A: Roundup <U+2013> Wizards; Court Awards $100,000 to Howard|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=November 13, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

After the [[1998<U+2013>99 NBA lockout]], the {{NBA Year|1998|team=Washington Wizards|title=Wizards}} posted an 18<U+2013>32 record in the shortened season. The team started out 13<U+2013>19 under Bickerstaff and was 5<U+2013>13 under [[Jim Brovelli]] after Bickerstaff was fired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/1999.html|title=1998<U+2013>99 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard was a vocal critic of Bickerstaff throughout his tenure, stating the coach was unable to make proper in-game adjustments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-04-08/sports/9904080312_1_all-stars-timeouts-bernie-bickerstaff|title=Bickerstaff Firing Shows Equality Thrives In Nba|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=April 8, 1999|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref> Howard, who again had an ankle injury,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-04-17/sports/9904170247_1_wizards-opponent-mci-center-washington-wizards|title=Bulls End Misery (for Washington): Wizards Look Miraculously Healed|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=April 17, 1999|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry}}</ref> missed the last 14&nbsp;games of the season. Over the course of the [[1998<U+2013>99 NBA season|1998<U+2013>99 season]], he posted 11&nbsp;double-doubles and two 15-rebound performances in 36&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH99GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1999/|title=Juwan Howard 1998<U+2013>99 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.9&nbsp;points and 7.0&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>

During the [[1999<U+2013>2000 NBA season|1999<U+2013>2000 season]], Howard accumulated 10&nbsp;double-doubles in 82&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH00GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2000/|title=Juwan Howard 1999<U+2013>2000 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 14.9&nbsp;points and 8.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  The {{NBA Year|1999|team=Washington Wizards|title=Wizards}} endured a 14<U+2013>30 start under head coach [[Gar Heard]] before going 15<U+2013>23 under Heard's replacement, [[Darrell Walker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/2000.html|title=1999<U+2013>00 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  According to [[Sam Smith (sportswriter)|Sam Smith]] from the ''Chicago Tribune'', Howard had become unpopular and a bit of a disappointment by his sixth season in Washington.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-01-07/sports/0001070183_1_juwan-howard-biggest-loser-million-contract-howard|title=Big Money Turns Howard Into Big Loser|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=January 7, 2000|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref>  He posted 30&nbsp;points twice,<ref name=JH00GL/> including a season-high 36 in a fourth-quarter comeback to end a five-game losing streak in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-01-22/sports/0001220154_1_juwan-howard-washington-wizards-indiana|title=Jordan Misses Wizards' Rally As Howard Helps Beat Pacers|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=January 22, 2000|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> During the offseason, Howard's name surfaced in trade rumors that had him going to the New York Knicks in exchange for Ewing because the Wizards' management thought that the trade would better position the team for the 2001 free agent market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2000/08/31/sports/pro-basketball-ewing-for-howard-is-latest-talk.html|title=Pro Basketball; Ewing for Howard Is Latest Talk|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=August 31, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Broussard, Chris}}</ref> Following the season, Walker was replaced by [[Leonard Hamilton]], becoming the team's sixth head coach since last making the [[NBA Playoffs]] four years earlier.<ref name=WboHac/>

Although it had been five years since his only All-Star appearance, Howard was the fourth-highest-paid player in the NBA during the [[2000<U+2013>01 NBA season|2000<U+2013>01 season]], behind [[Kevin Garnett]], [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and Mourning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-11-24/sports/0011240346_1_overpaid-patrick-ewing-scottie-pippen|title=The Nba's Top 20 Salaries|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=November 24, 2000|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref> Howard, along with Strickland and Richmond, were marquee names on the team under contract to earn at least $10 million.<ref name=WboHac>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2000-06-15/sports/0006150103_1_wizards-hamilton-college-coaches|title=Wizards bring on Hamilton as coach: Deal believed to be $10 million, 5 seasons Pro Basketball|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 15, 2000|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Ewell, Christian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2000-10-12/sports/0010120082_1_wizards-hamilton-juwan-howard|title=Questions hang in air as Wizards exit camp: But nothing's new about No. 1: How to turn around loser?|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 12, 2000|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Kent, Milton}}</ref> On December 31, 2000, Howard, posted his career high of 15&nbsp;made&nbsp;free&nbsp;throws in a game against the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Detroit Pistons|title=Detroit Pistons}}.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> Despite the fact that the February 11, [[2001 NBA All-Star Game]] was hosted by Washington at the MCI Center, Howard was not included on the Eastern Conference team even when it had to make two late additions ([[Anthony Mason (basketball)|Anthony Mason]] and [[Latrell Sprewell]]). According to Milton Kent of ''The Baltimore Sun'', not only did Howard's statistics (approximately 18 points, 7 rebounds and 2.8 assists) compare favorably to both players, but his role as his team's primary scoring option made his statistics more significant than those of Mason and Sprewell.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2001-02-04/sports/0102040234_1_juwan-howard-wizards-signed-howard|title=Howard merits nod as All-Star: Pro Basketball|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 4, 2001|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Kent, Milton}}</ref> Jordan, who had become the Wizards' head of basketball operations the prior season, traded Howard, [[Obinna Ekezie]], and [[Calvin Booth]] to the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Dallas Mavericks|title=Dallas Mavericks}} for Laettner, [[Loy Vaught]], [[Etan Thomas]], [[Hubert Davis]], [[Courtney Alexander]] and $3&nbsp;million on February 22, 2001, at the NBA trade deadline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-02-23/sports/0102230352_1_bulls-trading-nba-finals|title=Mutombo Deal Highlights Busy Day: Sixers Swap Ratliff, Kukoc To Hawks Bulls Remain Quiet|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=February 23, 2001|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/23/sports/pro-basketball-76ers-hope-mutombo-will-deliver-the-title.html|title=Pro Basketball; 76ers Hope Mutombo Will Deliver the Title|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=February 23, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Wise, Mike}}</ref>  Jordan's move was praised for freeing up salary cap space in advance of the NBA's first season with a luxury tax.<ref name=PBNTTTFaBT>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/25/sports/pro-basketball-notebook-trading-talent-today-for-a-better-tomorrow.html|title=Pro Basketball; Notebook; Trading Talent Today For a Better Tomorrow|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=February 25, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Wise, Mike}}</ref> The trade served the Mavericks by giving them a new offensive weapon and enabling them to match up defensively against the [[NBA Western Conference]] power forwards such as Wallace, [[Tim Duncan]], [[Karl Malone]] and Webber.<ref name=PBNTTTFaBT/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/23/sports/pro-basketball-76ers-hope-mutombo-will-deliver-the-title.html|title=Pro Basketball; 76ers Hope Mutombo Will Deliver the Title|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 23, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Wise, Mike}}</ref> Washington finished the year with a 19<U+2013>63 record under coach Hamilton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/2001.html|title=2000<U+2013>01 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>

===2001<U+2013>04===
During the 2000<U+2013>01 season, the Mavericks finished 53<U+2013>29 under coach [[Don Nelson]].<ref name=01MAVS>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DAL/2001.html|title=2000<U+2013>01 Dallas Mavericks Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard provided the Mavericks with a back-to-the-basket player who moved into the starting power-forward position, enabling [[Dirk Nowitzki]] to play small forward and [[Shawn Bradley]] to play center.<ref name=PBMHHSoS/> During the season, Howard tallied 16&nbsp;double-doubles and five 30-point performances in 81&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH01GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2001/|title=Juwan Howard 2000<U+2013>01 Game Log|accessdate=May 22, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.0&nbsp;points and 7.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  On a team with All-Star [[Michael Finley]] and future MVPs [[Steve Nash]] and Nowitzki, Howard was the highest-paid player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/dallas/mavericks/post/_/id/4669018/50-for-10-new-unis-new-tude-in-2001-02|title=50 for 10: New unis, new 'tude in 2001<U+2013>02|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=|author=Caplan, Jeff|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  On March 20, Howard blocked five shots, his career high, against the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Portland Trail Blazers|title=Portland Trail Blazers}}.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  In the [[2001 NBA Playoffs]], the Mavericks advanced past the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Utah Jazz|title=Utah Jazz}} 3 games to 2 before losing to the {{NBA Year|2000|team=San Antonio Spurs|title=San Antonio Spurs}}, 4 games to 1.<ref name=01MAVS/> The Utah games marked the first time Howard played for a team that won an NBA playoff series.<ref name=JHBR/> In the first game of the series against the Spurs, Howard slammed Spurs guard [[Derek Anderson (basketball)|Derek Anderson]] to the floor while trying to block Anderson's layup late in the game.<ref name=AndersonInjury>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/nba/01playoffs/confsemis/2001-05-05-spurs-mavs-game-1.htm|title=Spurs roll to Game 1 victory, but it's costly|last=Koidin|first=Michelle|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=July 14, 2010 | date=May 5, 2001}}</ref> Anderson suffered a separated shoulder on the play, and Howard received a flagrant foul and was ejected.<ref name=AndersonInjury /> After the game, Howard, Spurs coach [[Gregg Popovich]], and Mavs owner [[Mark Cuban]] all said the foul was committed without malice or intent to injure Anderson.<ref name=AndersonInjury /> In the Mavericks' 10 playoff games, Howard totaled three double-doubles while averaging 13.4&nbsp;points and 8.3&nbsp;rebounds in 39.1&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=JHBR/><ref name=JH01GL/>

During the [[2001<U+2013>02 NBA season|2001<U+2013>02 season]], he posted 17&nbsp;double-doubles and three 30-point performances in 81&nbsp;games (72&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH02GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2002/|title=Juwan Howard 2001<U+2013>02 Game Log|accessdate=May 22, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 14.6&nbsp;points and 7.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  This was the first time since his rookie holdout season that he did not start every game he played in.<ref name=JHBR/>  All reserve appearances occurred between November 21 and December 11, and eight of them were in consecutive games between November 21 and December 5.<ref name=JH02GL/> On January 31, he posted a career-high 16&nbsp;rebounds against the {{NBA Year|2001|team=Houston Rockets|title=Houston Rockets}}.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> The Mavericks traded him with [[Donnell Harvey]], Hardaway and a 2002 first-round pick to the {{NBA Year|2001|team=Denver Nuggets|title=Denver Nuggets}} for [[Raef LaFrentz]], [[Avery Johnson]], Van Exel and [[Tariq Abdul-Wahad]] on February 21, 2002.<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-02-22/sports/0202220344_1_frontier-league-contract-international-league|title=Baseball Major League Baseball MLB: Named Bob&nbsp;... |accessdate=May 24, 2010|date=February 22, 2002|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  At the time of the trade, Howard was considered the Mavericks' best low-post defender.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-02-25/sports/0202250183_1_mavs-nick-van-exel-los-angeles-lakers|title=Little 'D' in Big D is OK|accessdate=May 24, 2010|date=February 25, 2002|author=Smith, Sam|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> On March 25, 2002, he scored his 10,000th&nbsp;career point at [[Madison Square Garden]] against the [[2001<U+2013>02 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/career_statistics.html?nav=TextNavBar|title=Juwan Howard-5|accessdate=June 12, 2012|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> Howard started all 28&nbsp;games that he played for the Nuggets.<ref name=JH02GL/> Don Nelson's Mavericks went to the second round of the [[2002 NBA Playoffs]] after trading Howard,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DAL/2002.html|title=2001<U+2013>02 Dallas Mavericks Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while the Nuggets failed to make the playoffs under coaches [[Dan Issel]] and [[Mike Evans (basketball)|Mike Evans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DEN/2002.html|title=2001<U+2013>02 Denver Nuggets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> By the end of the season, Nuggets general manager Vandeweghe had cleared almost $20 million of salary cap space, leaving the team with few veterans and only Howard and [[Marcus Camby]] as well-known players. This made the team an undesirable coaching assignment for veteran coaches.<ref name=Accim/> In the offseason, the Nuggets replaced Evans with the relatively unknown [[Jeff Bzdelik]].<ref name=Accim>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2003-02-01/sports/0302010045_1_jeff-bzdelik-denver-nuggets-umbc|title=At center court, invisible man: NBA: Jeff Bzdelik's coaching career has taken him from UMBC to the Denver Nuggets, but one thing hasn't changed: his obscurity.|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 1, 2003|author=Markus, Don|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref>

During a preseason game, Howard attempted to punch [[Al Harrington]] and [[Jermaine O'Neal]], which earned him a suspension on October 25, 2002. As a result, Howard missed the {{NBA Year|2002|team=Denver Nuggets|title=Nuggets}}' first two games of the regular season, and this cost him $458,000 in salary.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/26/sports/plus-pro-basketball-nuggets-howard-suspended-and-fined.html|title=Plus: Pro Basketball; Nuggets' Howard Suspended and Fined|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 26, 2002|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Howard first attempted to hit Harrington late in the fourth quarter on a night when Howard had missed nine of ten shots. When O'Neal intervened, the two pushed and shoved each other before Howard started punching again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Sports_News/2002/10/25/Juwan-Howard-suspended-two-games/UPI-57721035590392/|title=Juwan Howard suspended two games|accessdate=June 12, 2012|date=October 25, 2002|agency=[[United Press International]]}}</ref> At around the same time, the University of Michigan basketball scandal investigation came to an end with many of the accomplishments of the Fab Five being rescinded through [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] sanctions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/11/08/sports/sports-of-the-times-forgetting-the-fab-five-is-impossible.html|title=Sports of The Times; Forgetting The Fab Five Is Impossible|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 8, 2002|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Rhoden, William C.}}</ref> Although many of the records of the Fab Five were erased, Howard's and teammate Rose's 1994 All-American recognitions were unaffected by the scandal.<ref name="MB07-8p13-21"/><ref name=MB07-8p154-5>{{cite book|title=2007<U+2013>08 Men's Basketball Media Guide|publisher=University of Michigan|pages=144<U+2013>5|year=2007}}</ref> During the [[2002<U+2013>03 NBA season|2002<U+2013>03 regular season]], he accumulated 18&nbsp;double-doubles, two 30-point performances, and three 15-rebound performances in 77&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH03GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2003/|title=Juwan Howard 2002<U+2013>03 Game Log|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.4&nbsp;points and 7.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/> The 2002<U+2013>03 Nuggets were 17<U+2013>65 under Bzdelik.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DEN/2003.html|title=2002<U+2013>03 Denver Nuggets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> The team struggled with the league's lowest payroll and three rookies in the starting lineup.<ref name=Accim/>  Howard started all 77&nbsp;games in which he played.<ref name=JH03GL/>

Howard signed what was believed to be a five-year, $28&nbsp;million contract as a free agent with the {{NBA Year|2003|team=Orlando Magic|title=Orlando Magic}} on July 16, 2003; he had been expected to sign with either Detroit or [[Minnesota Timberwolves|Minnesota]].<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2003-07-14/sports/0307140234_1_juwan-howard-magic-play-in-orlando|title=Howard Set To Join Magic: Veteran Forward Juwan Howard Reached An Oral Agreement With Orlando For A Five-year Contract.|accessdate=June 12, 2012|date=July 13, 2003|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|author=Brewer, Jerry}}</ref> During the season, teammate [[Tracy McGrady]] successfully defended his [[List of National Basketball Association season scoring leaders|scoring championship]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/tracy_mcgrady/bio.html|title=Tracy McGrady|accessdate=March 3, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> while Howard attempted to be a positive influence when the situation arose, such as when he attempted to stop McGrady from kicking the [[basketball (ball)|basketball]] into the stands twice in a row.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/games/2004-02-21-magic-nuggets_x.htm|title=Magic put a spell on Nuggets in 102<U+2013>98 win|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=February 21, 2004|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Branom, Mike}}</ref> McGrady missed the last 10 games of the season with knee problems (ending his season on March 24),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/mcgratr01/gamelog/2004/|title=Tracy McGrady 2003<U+2013>04 Game Log|accessdate=March 3, 2013|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> leading to Howard's best performances of the season: Howard had 33 points and 11 rebounds on April 2 against the {{NBA Year|2003|team=Atlanta Hawks|title=Atlanta Hawks}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?id=240402019|title=Atlanta 95, Orlando 87|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=April 2, 2004|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> and he had 38 points on April 12 against the {{NBA Year|2003|team=Chicago Bulls|title=Chicago Bulls}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=240412004|title=Fizer has 30 points, 20 boards in loss|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=April 12, 2004|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Over the course of the [[2003<U+2013>04 NBA season|2003<U+2013>04 season]], he had 16&nbsp;double-doubles and two 30-point performances in 81&nbsp;games (77&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH04GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2004/|title=Juwan Howard 2003<U+2013>04 Game Log|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 17.2&nbsp;points and 7.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  The team compiled a 21<U+2013>61 record, the worst in the NBA, under coaches [[Doc Rivers]] and [[Johnny Davis (basketball)|Johnny Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/ORL/2004.html|title=2003<U+2013>04 Orlando Magic Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/30/sports/pro-basketball-notebook-mcgrady-gets-wish-in-trade-to-rockets.html|title=Pro Basketball: Notebook; McGrady Gets Wish In Trade To Rockets|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=June 30, 2004|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Broussard, Chris}}</ref>

===Houston Rockets era (2004<U+2013>07)===
{{multiple image
| align     = right
| direction = horizontal
