On June 29, 2004, Howard and Magic teammates McGrady, [[Tyronn Lue]] and [[Reece Gaines]] were part of a seven-player trade that sent {{NBA Year|2003|team=Houston Rockets|title=2003<U+2013>04 Houston Rockets}} [[starting lineup|starting]] guards [[Steve Francis]] and [[Cuttino Mobley]], plus [[Kelvin Cato]], to the Magic.<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/2004-06-29-mcgrady-francis-deal_x.htm|title=McGrady-Francis swap official, finally|author=Denton, John Denton|date=June 30, 2004|accessdate=May 24, 2010|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> In late November, as a short term experiment,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/To-Van-Gundy-lack-of-praise-beats-feint-praise-1505420.php|title=To Van Gundy, lack of praise beats feint praise|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=December 2, 2004|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigan, Jonathan}}</ref> head coach  [[Jeff Van Gundy]] decided to reduce Howard's playing time so that [[Scott Padgett]] could move up in the rotation to backup power forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Situation-has-Van-Gundy-Rockets-at-a-loss-1955540.php|title=Situation has Van Gundy, Rockets at a loss|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=November 29, 2004|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigan, Jonathan}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Maurice Taylor]] started the first 16&nbsp;games of the season for the {{NBA Year|2004|team=Houston Rockets|title=Rockets}} at power forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/t/tayloma01/gamelog/2005/|title=Maurice Taylor 2004<U+2013>05 Game Log|accessdate=May 26, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Van Gundy was unsatisfied with his power forward rotation, so he made the first starting lineup change of the season not mandated by injury by putting Howard into the starting lineup ahead of Taylor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Talk-with-Van-Gundy-brings-out-best-in-T-Mac-1516767.php|title=Talk with Van Gundy brings out best in T-Mac|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=December 4, 2004|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigan, Jonathan}}</ref> Although Taylor was available and played,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=241202006|title=Rockets 106 (6<U+2013>11, 4<U+2013>6 away), Mavericks 113 (11<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3 home)|accessdate=May 26, 2010|date=December 2, 2004|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Howard became the regular starter on December 2 and started for the rest of the season,<ref name=JH05GL/> and the team traded Taylor before the trade deadline in February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=1998814|title=Knicks land Rose, Taylor, draft picks|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=February 24, 2005|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> 

The 2004<U+2013>05 Rockets were 51<U+2013>31 under Van Gundy and lost in the first round of the [[2005 NBA Playoffs]] to the {{NBA Year|2004|team=Dallas Mavericks|title=Dallas Mavericks}}, 4&nbsp;games to 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/2005.html|title=2004<U+2013>05 Houston Rockets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Although the Rockets made the playoffs, Howard's season ended on March 14, when he left a game with a sprained [[medial collateral ligament]] (MCL) in his right knee.<ref name=JH05GL/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-03-15/sports/0503150291_1_injury-report-tracy-mcgrady-rasheed-wallace|title=Nugget OK with benching|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=March 15, 2005|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> Initially, the injury was supposed to sideline Howard for four weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Howard-feels-lost-without-Rockets-1946051.php|title=Howard feels lost without Rockets|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=March 17, 2005|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Manfull, Megan}}</ref> The injury coincided with a period in which he developed symptoms of [[viral myocarditis]], including heart [[palpitation]]s, mild chest pains and fever and was diagnosed with a viral infection in his heart. His limited physical activity impaired his MCL rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-04-07/sports/0504070359_1_viral-infection-rockets-juwan-howard|title=Season over for Howard: Rockets forward shut down by viral infection in heart|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=April 7, 2005|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> Over the course of the [[2004<U+2013>05 NBA season|2004<U+2013>05 season]], Howard achieved seven double-doubles in 61&nbsp;games (47&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH05GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2005/|title=Juwan Howard 2004<U+2013>05 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 9.6&nbsp;points and 5.7&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  His 26.6&nbsp;minutes per game marked the first season that he played less than 32&nbsp;minutes per game.<ref name=JHBR/>

During the [[2005<U+2013>06 NBA season|2005<U+2013>06 season]], Howard recorded 10&nbsp;double-doubles and two 30-point performances in 80&nbsp;games (all as a starter),<ref name=JH06GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2006/|title=Juwan Howard 2005<U+2013>06 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 11.8&nbsp;points and 6.7&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  He played 31.7&nbsp;minutes per game, and this was the last season in which he averaged 30&nbsp;minutes per game; this was also the final season in which Howard started at least half of the games in which he played.<ref name=JHBR/> The {{NBA Year|2005|team=Houston Rockets|title=Rockets}} were 34<U+2013>48 under Van Gundy and missed the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/2006.html|title=2005<U+2013>06 Houston Rockets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> Howard was suspended one game without pay in January for shoving the basketball into the face of Toronto guard [[Mike James]] in an exchange that occurred after Howard fouled James on a drive to the basket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-01-08/sports/0601080409_1_shoving-juwan-howard-rockets|title=NBA orders Howard to sit 1 game|accessdate=June 10, 2012|date=January 8, 2006|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> On April 10, [[Yao Ming]] suffered a season-ending broken foot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Broken-foot-ends-Yao-s-year-1864532.php|title=Broken foot ends Yao's year|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 11, 2006|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> In Yao's absence, Howard posted a season-high 31 points on April 17 against the [[Denver Nuggets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Howard-shines-as-Rockets-edge-Nuggets-1657775.php|title=Howard shines as Rockets edge Nuggets|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 17, 2006|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Pells, Eddie}}</ref>

In the [[2006<U+2013>07 NBA season|2006<U+2013>07 season]], Howard achieved nine double-doubles in 80&nbsp;games played (37&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH07GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2007/|title=Juwan Howard 2006<U+2013>07 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 9.7&nbsp;points and 5.9&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=RctrgJfH>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-close-to-re-acquiring-guard-James-for-1604258.php|title=Rockets close to re-acquiring guard James for Howard|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 13, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> During the season, he lost the starting power forward position to [[Chuck Hayes]], but got back in the starting lineup when Yao got injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-complete-trade-to-bring-James-back-1793964.php|title=Rockets complete trade to bring James back|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 14, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Elliot, Christopher}}</ref>  His 26.5&nbsp;minutes per game marked a new career low.<ref name=JHBR/> Howard only started 38 games,<ref name=RctrgJfH/> including 32 consecutive starts between December 26, 2006, and March 3, 2007,<ref name=JH07GL/> while center Yao was recovering from his fractured right leg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/mingya01/gamelog/2007/|title=Yao Ming 2006<U+2013>07 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-rout-Nets-to-halt-two-game-skid-1868729.php|title=Rockets rout Nets to halt two-game skid: Battier makes career-high seven three-pointers, leads Rockets with 23 points|accessdate=June 17, 2012|date=December 27, 2006|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> The 2006<U+2013>07 Rockets were 52<U+2013>30 under Van Gundy for the regular season.<ref name=HOU07/> The Rockets entered the [[2007 NBA Playoffs]] with little experience; Howard was one of only three players on the team (along with [[Rafer Alston]] and [[Dikembe Mutombo]]) to have previously won any NBA playoff series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-open-postseason-hungry-for-series-win-1844893.php|title=Rockets open postseason hungry for series win|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 21, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> Once the playoffs began, Howard served as a key reserve on the Rockets' short bench rotation that also included [[Luther Head]] and Mutombo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/ROCKETS-NOTES-Yao-says-team-lacked-intensity-1830685.php|title=Rockets Notes: Yao says team lacked intensity|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 30, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Blinebury, Fran and Jonathan Feigen}}</ref> The Rockets managed to split the first 4 games even though Head and Howard only combined to average 7.6 points,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-know-they-were-outworked-by-Jazz-1825653.php|title=Rockets know they were outworked by Jazz|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 30, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/NOTES-Rockets-guard-against-looking-ahead-1543958.php|title=Notes: Rockets guard against looking ahead|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 1, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> including a combined pointless 0-for-10 game three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-reserves-unable-to-give-starters-any-1611859.php|title=Rockets reserves unable to give starters any support|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 27, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Solomon, Jerome}}</ref> Although Howard had a productive game five with 12 points and 6 rebounds which contributed to a Rockets victory,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Howard-Head-team-up-to-outscore-Jazz-reserves-1793701.php|title=Howard, Head team up to outscore Jazz reserves|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=May 1, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Solomon, Jerome}}</ref> the team lost in the first round of the 2007 playoffs to the {{NBA Year|2006|team=Utah Jazz|title=Utah Jazz}}, four games to three.<ref name=HOU07>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/2007.html|title=2006<U+2013>07 Houston Rockets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  In the playoffs, reserve Howard averaged 5.0&nbsp;points and 4.4&nbsp;rebounds in 22.4&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=JHBR/><ref name=JH07GL/> Although Howard was described as a consistent role player and locker-room leader,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4366410|title=James makes Rockets return / Alston will vie with childhood pal for point guard role; Howard heading to Timberwolves|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=June 15, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Elliott, Chris|page=13, sports section}}</ref> his salary continued to be perceived as outrageous by sportswriters such as the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''{{'s}} Jerome Solomon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4382516|title=No bones about it: Rockets being smart|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=July 11, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Solomon, Jerome|page=2, sports section|quote=Yes, the Rockets traded Juwan Howard and his ridiculous contract to bring Mike James back to his adopted home.}}</ref>

===2007<U+2013>10===
On June 14, 2007, Howard was traded to the [[2007<U+2013>08 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota Timberwolves]] for James and [[Justin Reed]].<ref name="rocketstrade">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2903593|title=Wolves, Rockets agree to Howard-James trade|author=Stein, Mark|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=June 14, 2007}}</ref>  According to ESPN, he regretted not choosing Minnesota the last time he had been a free agent and was looking forward to playing with Garnett.<ref name="noyouth">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3086024|title=Wolves get younger with buyout of Howard's contract|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 29, 2007}}</ref>  Soon after Howard signed with Minnesota, the team traded Garnett to the [[2007<U+2013>08 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/g/garneke01.html|title=Kevin Garnett|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> Howard made it clear he was not interested in being on a team in Minnesota that was focused on developing young talent and consequently requested a trade once Garnett was no longer a member of the team.<ref name="noyouth" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Zgoda, Jerry|url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/wolves/11695546.html?elr=KArksUUUoDEy3LGDiO7aiU|title=Juwan Howard: A reluctant <U+2013> but respectful <U+2013> Wolf: Juwan Howard would like to be traded. But if the Wolves can't make a deal, the veteran will be a mentor to his young teammates|work=[[Star Tribune]]|accessdate=October 8, 2010|date=September 28, 2007}}</ref>  Howard still had $6.88&nbsp;million and $7.38&nbsp;million in salary owed to him over the next two seasons, which made him difficult to trade.<ref name="noyouth"/> Timberwolves owner [[Glen Taylor]] noted that the team would attempt to accommodate his wishes but acknowledged that doing so would be difficult.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolves Trying To Trade Howard|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=August 23, 2007|page=D2}}</ref> On October 29, 2007, the Timberwolves [[NBA Salary Cap#Waivers|waived]] Howard after agreeing to a contractual buyout agreement<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news?slug=txtimberwolveshoward&prov=st&type=lgns|title=Timberwolves waive F Howard after reaching buyout|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 29, 2007|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]}}</ref> worth $10&nbsp;million spread over four years instead of the roughly $14.25&nbsp;million ($6.88&nbsp;million plus $7.38&nbsp;million) that Minnesota would otherwise have owed him.<ref name=FkwW>{{cite web|author=Youngblood, Kent|url=http://www.startribune.com/511/story/1516287.html|title=Foye's knee worries Wolves|work=[[Star Tribune]]|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 30, 2007}}</ref>

[[File:20080125 Juwan Howard signing autographs.jpg|thumb|left|Howard signing [[autograph]]s as a [[Dallas Maverick]]|alt=Black man mingles with the fans]]
Howard agreed to terms with the [[2007<U+2013>08 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas Mavericks]] on October 30, 2007, but was not able to officially sign until the next day, when he cleared waivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3087419|title=Mavs agree to terms with free-agent forward Juwan Howard|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 30, 2007|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4452643|title=NBA Notes|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 31, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|page=4, sports section}}</ref> Terms of the deal were not disclosed publicly. During the [[2007<U+2013>08 NBA season|2007<U+2013>08 season]], he played in 50&nbsp;games and made no starts,<ref name=JH08GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2008/|title=Juwan Howard 2007<U+2013>08 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 1.1&nbsp;points and 1.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/> In his limited role he never played more than 18&nbsp;minutes and had season-highs of seven rebounds and six points.<ref name=JH08GL/>  The 2007<U+2013>08 Mavericks were 51<U+2013>31 under coach Johnson and lost in the first round of the [[2008 NBA Playoffs]] to the [[2007<U+2013>08 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans Hornets]] four games to one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DAL/2008.html|title=2007<U+2013>08 Dallas Mavericks Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> In the playoffs, Howard only appeared for a total of 11&nbsp;minutes in three games.<ref name=JHBR/> This was the first season in Howard's career in which he did not start in a single game.<ref name=JHBR/>

On October 3, 2008,<ref name=JHBR/> Howard rejoined the [[2008<U+2013>09 Denver Nuggets season|Denver Nuggets]], but was later released when the Nuggets made a three-for-one trade of [[Allen Iverson]] for [[Chauncey Billups]], [[Antonio McDyess]] and [[Cheikh Samb]] on November 3 that put them over the 15-man roster size limit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-11-04/sports/0811030532_1_varsity-softball-coach-football-coach-options|title=Transactions|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=November 4, 2008|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  When he was waived, Howard was the only player on the Nuggets' roster without a guaranteed contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-11-04/sports/0811030510_1_cheikh-samb-nuggets-pistons|title=Allen Iverson trade brings extra challenge for Derrick Rose|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=November 4, 2008|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Johnson, K. C.}}</ref> Before the trade, Howard had played in three games during the [[2008<U+2013>09 NBA season|2008<U+2013>09 season]]. His appearances had all come from off the bench and lasted between 7 and 8 minutes.<ref name=JH09GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2009/|title=Juwan Howard 2008<U+2013>09 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  After Howard departed, the Nuggets went on to post a 54<U+2013>28 record and reach the Western Conference finals under [[George Karl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DEN/2009.html|title=2008<U+2013>09 Denver Nuggets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> On December 12, 2008, he was signed by the [[2008<U+2013>09 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte Bobcats]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/bobcats/release_howard_signed_081212.html |title=Bobcats Sign Juwan Howard |accessdate=December 12, 2008 |publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> During the 2008<U+2013>09 season, he played in 42&nbsp;games, making two starts;<ref name="JH09GL"/> Howard averaged 4.1&nbsp;points and 1.8&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  In his reserve role, he played more than 20&nbsp;minutes five times, including four straight appearances from January 28 to February 8, and had season-highs of five rebounds and 14&nbsp;points. He posted 10 or more points five times.<ref name=JH09GL/>  Howard played extended minutes on January 28, the night after [[Gerald Wallace]] suffered a left-lung collapse and a non-displaced fracture of the fifth rib from a [[flagrant foul]] by [[Andrew Bynum]]; in 24 minutes of action, he scored 9 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=290128022|title=Aldridge helps Blazers win third straight contest|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=January 28, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name=WiicwB>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3866849|title=Wallace injured in collision with Bynum|accessdate=June 19, 2012|date=January 29, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=290128022|title=Bobcats 74 (19<U+2013>27, 6<U+2013>14 away); Trail Blazers 88 (28<U+2013>17, 17<U+2013>5 home)|accessdate=June 19, 2012|date=January 28, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> During Howard's streak of 20-minute appearances,<ref name="JH09GL"/> he sat out one intervening game on February 6 with a toe injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=290206030|title=Hawks rally from 17-point deficit to drop slumping Bobcats|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=February 6, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On February 8, in only his second start as a Bobcat, he played a season-high 30 minutes, 39 seconds and posted a season-high 14&nbsp;points.<ref name=JH09GL/>  The subsequent night, Howard was out of the lineup again with a toe injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=290209030|title=Radmanovic hits 3 late 3s in debut as Bobcats end 5-game slide|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=February 9, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  The 2008<U+2013>09 Bobcats were 35<U+2013>47 under coach [[Larry Brown (basketball)|Larry Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/CHA/2009.html|title=2008<U+2013>09 Charlotte Bobcats Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>

[[File:20100425 Juwan Howard against Amar'e Stoudemire.jpg|thumb|Howard as a [[Portland Trail Blazers|Portland Trail Blazer]] against [[Amar'e Stoudemire]]|alt=Black athlete holds a basketball while a defender with his back to the camera plays defense]]
On September 17, 2009, Howard signed a one-year contract with the [[2009<U+2013>10 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2009/news/09/17/blazers.howard.ap/index.html|title=Trail Blazers sign Juwan Howard to one-year deal|publisher=National Basketball Association|accessdate=September 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.nba.com/blazers/news/trail_blazers_sign_juwan_howar_2009_09_17.html|title=Trail Blazers Sign Juwan Howard|publisher=Portland Trail Blazers
|date=September 17, 2009|accessdate=September 17, 2009}}</ref>  On December 22, center [[Joel Przybilla]] injured his knee in the first quarter, allowing Howard to play additional minutes,<ref name=TBrbRAtoMiDr>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=291222006|title=Trail Blazers rally behind Roy, Aldridge to overcome Mavs in Dirk's return|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=December 22, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  which allowed Howard his first double-double since April 6, 2007.<ref name=TBrbRAtoMiDr/>  He had his other double-double of the 2009<U+2013>10 season the next night when he made his first start of the season.<ref name=JH08GL/>  All of Howard's performances with 10&nbsp;rebounds or more occurred between December 22 and February 3. December 23 marked the start of 14 consecutive starting appearances and 24&nbsp;starts in 26&nbsp;appearances (ending on February 16) for him.<ref name=JH10GL/> Having lost Przybilla and [[Greg Oden]] for the season, Portland acquired Camby from the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] for [[Steve Blake]] and [[Travis Outlaw]] on February 17 prior to the trade deadline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=4918893|title=Clippers get two players for Camby|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=February 17, 2010|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> During the [[2009<U+2013>10 NBA season|2009<U+2013>10 season]], he accumulated two double-doubles, played in 73&nbsp;games, and made 27&nbsp;starts,<ref name=JH10GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2010/|title=Juwan Howard 2009<U+2013>10 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 6.0&nbsp;points and 4.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  The 2009<U+2013>10 Trail Blazers were 50<U+2013>32 under coach [[Nate McMillan]] and lost in the first round of the [[2010 NBA Playoffs]] to the [[2009<U+2013>10 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix Suns]], four games to two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/POR/2010.html|title=2009<U+2013>10 Portland Trail Blazers Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard appeared in all six games, averaging 3.3&nbsp;points and 2.7&nbsp;rebounds in 14.5&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=JHBR/> He played the most minutes (17:51) in game 4,<ref name=JH10GL/> when he added 8 points and 7 rebounds to help even the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=300424022|title=Suns 87 (2<U+2013>2, 1<U+2013>1 away); Trail Blazers 96 (2<U+2013>2, 1<U+2013>1 home)|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 24, 2010|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

===Miami Heat era (2010<U+2013>present)===
On July 20, 2010, Howard came to terms for the [[2010<U+2013>11 NBA season]] with the [[2010<U+2013>11 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]] on a one-year contract for the veteran's minimum salary, which was $1,352,181.<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=5396136|title=Howard signs with Heat <U+2013> again|accessdate=July 21, 2010|date=July 20, 2010|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/roster/heat_signs_juwan_howard_2010_07_20.html|title=Heat Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=July 20, 2010|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref>  Although he was only paid the minimum by the Heat, he was in the final year of his four-year buyout from the Timberwolves.<ref name=FkwW/> By joining the Heat, Howard joined a team that by the time of the [[2011 NBA playoffs]], included former champion [[Dwyane Wade]] as well as a group of players such as [[LeBron James]] and [[Chris Bosh]] who had not won an NBA championship despite numerous All-Star game selections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://offthedribble.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/02/keeping-score-they-won-a-lot-of-games-and-soon-a-title/|title=Keeping Score: They Won a Lot of Games, and Soon a Title|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 2, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Paine, Neil}}</ref> In March, he was featured in the documentary film ''[[The Fab Five (film)|The Fab Five]]'', which was about his time as a Wolverine, that reignited controversy and reinvigorated the [[Duke<U+2013>Michigan basketball rivalry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequad.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/14/documentary-rekindles-fab-five-memories/|title=Documentary Rekindles 'Fab Five' Memories|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=March 14, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Gerstner, Joanne C.}}</ref> On March 31, Howard was fined $35,000 for escalating an altercation the night before. Howard was ejected for pushing [[JaVale McGee]], who was attempting to break up a dispute between [[Zydrunas Ilgauskas]] and [[John Wall (basketball)|John Wall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chicagotribune.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=chicagosports&page=nba/news/newstest.aspx?id=4393018|title=Wall suspended one game for altercation with Ilgauskas|accessdate=June 20, 2012|date=March 31, 2011|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=310330027|title=John Wall ejected for fracas in Wizards' loss vs. Heat|accessdate=June 20, 2012|date=March 30, 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> For the season, Howard played 57 games for the [[2010<U+2013>11 Miami Heat season|2010<U+2013>11 Heat]], all as a reserve. He averaged 2.4 points and 2.1 rebounds with season highs of 18 points and 7 rebounds.<ref name=JH11GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2011/|title=Juwan Howard 2010<U+2013>11 Game Log|accessdate=June 20, 2012|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> The Heat reached the NBA Finals, losing to the Dallas Mavericks four games to two.<ref name="MVP">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/06/12/nowitzki-finals-mvp.ap/index.html|title=Gutty performance earns Nowitzki Finals MVP honors|date=June 12, 2011|publisher=National Basketball Association|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref><ref name="Washington Post">{{cite news|title=NBA Finals: Dirk Nowitzki and the Dallas Mavericks complete stunning run to the championship|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/wizards/nba-finals-dirk-nowitzki-and-the-dallas-mavericks-complete-stunning-run-to-the-championship/2011/06/12/AGrwtPSH_story.html|accessdate=June 13, 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Lee |first=Michael |date=June 12, 2011}}</ref> Howard averaged 1.5 points and .9 rebounds per game during the postseason.<ref name=JHBR/>

On December 10, 2011, Howard re-signed with the Heat for the same veteran's minimum salary as the year before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/miamiheat/post/_/id/10494/the-heats-big-void-lingers-front-and-center|title=The Heat's big void lingers, front and center|accessdate=December 12, 2011|date=December 10, 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Windhorst, Brian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/#!/SpearsNBAYahoo/status/145244461851619328|title=@SpearsNBAYahoo status|accessdate=December 12, 2011|date=December 9, 2011|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Spears, Marc J.}}</ref> Howard appeared in 28 regular season games as a reserve with limited minutes.<ref name=JH12GL>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2012/|title=Juwan Howard 2011<U+2013>12 Game Log|accessdate=June 20, 2012|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> At age 39, Howard was the third-oldest active player in the league during the [[2011<U+2013>12 NBA season]], behind [[Kurt Thomas (basketball)|Kurt Thomas]] and [[Grant Hill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/dallas/mavericks/post/_/id/4685166/six-pack-vince-carter-moves-up-scoring-list|title=Six-Pack: Vince Carter moves up scoring list|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 16, 2012|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Stein, Marc}}</ref> Before Game 4 of an [[2012 NBA playoffs]] series against the [[2011<U+2013>12 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]], Howard engaged in pregame verbal sparring with [[Lance Stephenson]] after Stephenson mocked Howard's teammate James.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/blog/eye-on-basketball/19104550/juwan-howard-and-lance-stephenson-in-game-4-pregame-verbal-altercation|title=Juwan Howard and Lance Stephenson in Game 4 pregame verbal altercation|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 20, 2012|author=Young, Royce|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]}}</ref> Despite this incident, Howard was a maturing influence on the team during the playoffs; according to David Neal of ''[[The Miami Herald]]'', "More often, Howard stood as the body of reason <U+2014> getting between Dwyane Wade and [[Erik Spoelstra|Spoelstra]] against Indiana in Game 3 of the second round, pulling [[Mario Chalmers]] away from [[2011<U+2013>12 Oklahoma City Thunder season|Oklahoma City]] star [[Kevin Durant]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/27/2868195/miami-heats-juwan-howard-finally.html|title=Miami Heat's Juwan Howard finally captures a title for the Michigan Fab Five|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 27, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Neal, David J.}}</ref> On June 21, 2012, Howard became the first and only member of the Fab Five to win an NBA championship, as a role player on the [[2011<U+2013>12 Miami Heat season|2011<U+2013>12 Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/06/23/juwan-howard-is-first-member-of-michigans-fab-five-to-win-nba-title/|title=Juwan Howard is first member of Michigan's "Fab Five" to win NBA title|accessdate=June 24, 2012|date=June 23, 2012|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|author=Martin, Daniel}}</ref> Howard was on the court as time expired in the series-clinching game because the three stars of the Heat (James, Wade and Bosh) had arranged it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/27/2868194_p3/miami-heat-2012-roster-breakdown.html|title=Miami Heat 2012 roster breakdown|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=June 27, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Jackson, Barry}}</ref> Howard spoke about representing the Fab Five after the Heat won the [[2012 NBA Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/post/_/id/46563/juwan-howard-the-fab-age-patch|title=Juwan Howard: The Fab-age Patch|accessdate=June 26, 2012|date=June 25, 2012|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Adande, J.A.}}</ref> A teammate with the Heat was [[Shane Battier]], who grew up in Detroit as a fan of the [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]] and idolized Howard. In his early teens, Battier sought Howard's [[autograph]] on a pair of sneakers and a few years later became a part of the Duke<U+2013>Michigan basketball rivalry when he turned down the local scholarship offer from Michigan to play for [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/20/sports/basketball/nba-finals-battier-and-howard-united-in-bid-for-championship-ring.html?ref=juwanhoward&_r=0|title=Split by Rivalry, United in Bid for a Ring|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 19, 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Araton, Harvey}}</ref> Following the season, Howard became an unrestricted free agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/07/01/2875839/turiaf-opts-out-of-heat-contract.html|title=Ronny Turiaf opts out of Miami Heat contract, but Dexter Pittman will be retained|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=July 1, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Jackson, Barry}}</ref> At the 20th annual [[ESPY Awards]], Howard and Heat teammate [[Mike Miller (basketball player)|Mike Miller]] took to the stage to accept the award for Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/07/15/2895813_p2/lets-just-say-us-wont-win-gold.html|title=Let's just say U.S. won<U+2019>t win gold for its uniforms|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=July 15, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Cote, Greg}}</ref> 

On February 21, 2013, the Heat traded [[Dexter Pittman]] to create space on the roster to pursue a more experienced big man.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nba-ball-dont-lie/miami-heat-trade-dexter-pittman-2013-2nd-round-201748524--nba.html|title=Miami Heat trade Dexter Pittman, 2013 2nd-round pick to Memphis Grizzlies for basically nothing|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=February 21, 2013|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|author=Devine, Dan}}</ref> On March 2, 2013, Howard signed a 10-day contract with the [[2012<U+2013>13 Miami Heat season|2012<U+2013>13 Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/roster/heat-signs-juwan-howard|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=March 2, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2013/news/03/02/heat-sign-howard.ap/index.html|title=Veteran Howard returns to Heat on 10-day contract|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=March 2, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> On March 12, 2013, he signed a second 10-day contract with the Heat,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/heat-signs-juwan-howard-second-10-day-contract|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard to Second 10-day Contract|accessdate=March 12, 2013|date=March 12, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> and on March 22, 2013, he was signed for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/heat-signs-juwan-howard|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=March 22, 2013|date=March 22, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> He made his first appearance of the season for the Heat on March 24 against the [[2012<U+2013>13 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte Bobcats]] tallying two points, a rebound and two assists in three minutes of play as the Heat made their way to their 26th consecutive victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400278761|title=Dwyane Wade-less Heat throttle Bobcats, run streak to 26|accessdate=2013-03-26|date=2013-03-24|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=400278761|title=Bobcats 77 (16-54, 6-29 away); Heat 109 (55-14, 32-3 home)|accessdate=2013-03-26|date=2013-03-24|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

==Personal==
[[File:Juwan Howard1-crop.jpg|left|thumb|Howard in 2008]]
Howard has remained a Chicago resident throughout his NBA career. In 1996, he bought a {{convert|3116|sqft|m2|1|adj=on}} [[town home]] for $490,000 in the South [[Loop, Chicago|Loop]] area that he had not sold, {{asof|2013|lc=on}}.<ref name="house">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-01-03/news/0912310497_1_chicago-river-floor-bulls|title=NBA star Juwan Howard buys condo in Trump tower|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=January 3, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Goldsborough, Bob}}</ref> In 2009, he paid $2.55&nbsp;million for a three-bedroom, {{convert|3080|sqft|m2|1|adj=on}} unit in the [[Trump International Hotel and Tower (Chicago)|Trump International Hotel & Tower]].<ref name="house"/> In 2005, Howard bought a {{convert|3.5|acre|m2|adj=on}} $11.775 million property in South Florida's Gables Estates, where he intended to build a {{convert|15000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} home, with a dock for a newly purchased {{convert|54|ft|m|adj=on}} [[yacht]] named the Fab 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10C2B98B0EEE3078&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=NBA Player Joining Ritzy Gables Enclave|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=August 21, 2005|page=4A, Front section|format=Subscription required}}</ref> After the Heat won the 2012 NBA championship, Howard sold the home within a week for about $10 million, but he continued to own at least one South Florida real estate property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/07/12/2892496/broward-commissioner-chip-lamarca.html|title=Broward commissioner Chip LaMarca facing foreclosure on house|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=July 12, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Lambiet, Jose}}</ref>

Howard's son, Juwan Howard, Jr. (born February 5, 1992),<ref name=JHJWMU>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmubroncos.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4600&ATCLID=204997509|title=Juwan Howard Jr.|accessdate=October 6, 2010|publisher=[[Western Michigan University]]}}</ref> is the child of Markita Blyden, who was runner-up for Michigan's Miss Basketball when she and her twin sister led Detroit's [[Murray Wright High School]] to the 1990 Class A state championship game. Howard, Jr. finished his senior season at Detroit's [[Pershing High School]] in spring 2010.<ref name=Hfiff>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/basketball/mens/news/story?id=4848717|title=Howard follows in family's footsteps|author=Arnold, Jeff|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=January 29, 2010|accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> As a junior, he led his high school to the [[Michigan High School Athletic Association]] state championship. As a senior, he was named first team All-State by the Associated Press and ''[[Detroit Free Press]]''.<ref name=JHJWMU/>  He played his freshman season for the [[2010<U+2013>11 Western Michigan Broncos men's basketball team|2010<U+2013>11 Western Michigan Broncos]] before he transferred to the [[University of Detroit Mercy]] [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Titans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/7057951/juwan-howard-jr-transfers-detroit-titans-western-michigan-broncos|title=Juwan Howard Jr. to play at Detroit|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 4, 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> As a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] sophomore for the [[2012<U+2013>13 Detroit Titans men's basketball team|2012<U+2013>13 Detroit Titans]], he became a regular starter and solid contributor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/02/26/3255084/nba-sons-making-their-mark-in.html#storylink=misearch|title=NBA sons making their mark in college basketball|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 26, 2013|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Beard, Aaron}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/51634/juwan-howard-jr|title=Juwan Howard Jr.|accessdate=March 1, 2013|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

On July 6, 2002, Howard married Jenine Wardally. At the time, Howard was 29 and Wardally was 27. They have two sons: Jace, who was born in late September 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F61BBC171E9EC9E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Miamian Finds Niche In TV Role|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=September 14, 2002|page=1B, Local section|format=Subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=RM&p_theme=rm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F733F8CD20B2918&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Howard Tells Teammates He's Sorry, And Rarin' To Go|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=November 5, 2002|work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|author=Tomasson, Chris}}</ref> and Jett, who is two years younger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11A50587EDB0C700&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=An Old Restaurant Starts A New Casino|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=July 4, 2007|page=4A, Front section|format=Subscription required}}</ref>

===Humanitarianism===

As a student athlete at the University of Michigan, Howard volunteered to visit patients at the [[University of Michigan Health System|University of Michigan Health System Hopitals]] in Ann Arbor, Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-02-11/sports/1996042075_1_juwan-howard-bullets-michigan|title=Howard's impact is felt on, off court Uncertain future: Juwan Howard has made an impression on those whose lives he has touched, and on a Bullets team needing a spark. But he will become a free agent after this season.|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 11, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> While juggling professional basketball duties and coursework as an NBA rookie/student-athlete, he continued to find time for charity work and hospital visits.<ref name=TADHKHPTHG/> His humanitarian works included a Stay in School Jam for 6,500 local area students that he participated in along with several teammates and rap artist [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-02-26/sports/1995057184_1_calbert-cheaney-baltimore-county-juwan-howard|title=Bullets at 'School Jam' tomorrow|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 26, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref> 

Howard is active in fostering youth basketball activities through the Juwan Howard Foundation, which helps underprivileged youth in Washington, DC and Chicago. He was recognized in 2001 as one of the "Good Guys in Sports" by ''[[The Sporting News]]'' for his civic contributions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/bio.html|title= Juwan Howard # Forward |accessdate=September 6, 2010|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/mavericks/news/good_guys_2001.html|title=Howard/Finley Named to TSN''s Good Guys List for 2001|accessdate=July 18, 2012|date=July 12, 2001|publisher=[[Dallas Mavericks]]}}</ref> In April 2010, Howard won the NBA Cares Community Assist Award for his community efforts, philanthropic work and charitable contributions.<ref name=PTBFCJHRNCCAAfA>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamatrailblazersfan.com/ArticleDisplay/tabid/120/ItemID/1442/Default.aspx|title=Portland Trail Blazers Forward/Center Juwan Howard Receives NBA Cares Community Assist Award for April|accessdate=September 6, 2010|date=April 30, 2010|publisher=[[Portland Trail Blazers]]/NBA Media Ventures, LLC}}</ref> He runs a yearly free basketball camp for youth, which is made possible by a partnership between the Juwan Howard Foundation and the [[Chicago Public Schools]] (CPS), Jordan Brand, [[Dell Computers]], [[EMI Music]], [[Vitamin Water]] and the NBA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/a1HroHKyEd6OEwAcxJTdpg/illinois--former-chicago-star-juwan-howard-returns-with-camp.htm|title= Illinois: Former Chicago Star Juwan Howard Returns With Camp: Football heats up with Bolingbrook's annual passing jamboree.|accessdate=September 6, 2010|date=July 19, 2009|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|work=[[MaxPreps]]|author=Bowker, Paul}}</ref> His foundation partners with the CPS for a reading challenge; the top 300 readers, out of 30,000 annually, attend his camp.<ref name=PTBFCJHRNCCAAfA/> During and after his time as a member of the Heat, Howard was active in South Florida community outreach, fundraising and humanitarian efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/18/2856376/nba-partners-renovate-miami-springs.html|title=NBA, partners renovate Miami Springs community center|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 18, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/10/26/3068996/was-scott-disick-shopping-for.html|title=Was Scott Disick shopping for a diamond?|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 26, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Abravanel, Lesley}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/12/29/3158627/heatnba-visit-to-the-springs-top.html|title=Heat/NBA visit to the Springs top story of 2012|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=December 29, 2012|work=River Cities Gazette|publisher[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Curtis, Tom & Bill Daley}}</ref>

==Film and television appearances==
Howard appeared in the 1994 basketball film ''[[Hoop Dreams]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blazersedge.com/2009/9/17/1035743/your-newest-blazer|title=Your Newest Blazer: Juwan Howard|accessdate=October 3, 2010|date=September 17, 2009|agency=Associated Press|author=Golliver, Ben}}</ref> He had a small role in the television drama ''[[The West Wing (TV series)|The West Wing]]'', appearing in the 1999 episode "[[The Crackpots and These Women]]" as Mr. Grant,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0745690/fullcredits|accessdate=June 3, 2010|title="The West Wing" The Crackpots and These Women (1999)|publisher=[[IMDB]].com}}</ref> a former [[Duke basketball]] player who served on [[Josiah Bartlet]]'s [[President's Council on Fitness, Sports, and Nutrition |Council on Fitness]] and helped him win a game against his staff.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=kTZsRcwe5mAC&pg=PA117&lpg=PA117&dq=Juwan+Howard+%22West+Wing%22#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Inside the West Wing: an unauthorized look at television's smartest show|accessdate=September 7, 2010|author=Challen, Paul|publisher=Ecw Press|isbn=1-55022-468-9|year=2001}}</ref>

Other appearances include the August 15, 1999 "The Art of Give and Take" episode of ''[[Arli$$]]'', the season 5 (2005) "Michigan's Fab 5" episode of ''[[Beyond the Glory]]'', the November 9, 1996 season 2 "Son-in-Law" episode of ''[[Hang Time (TV series)|Hang Time]]'' and the 2011 documentary ''[[The Fab Five (film)|The Fab Five]]'', produced by his Michigan teammate Jalen Rose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/juwan-howard/248685|title=Juwan Howard|accessdate=October 3, 2010|work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode | title = Son-in-Law | series = Hang Time | serieslink = Hang Time (TV series) | network = [[NBC]] | airdate = November 9, 1996 | season = 2 | number = 10}}</ref><!--Actual refs are spam and non-RS so I cited the episode under the assumption he really appeared on the show<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvrage.com/shows/id-3783/printable/|title=Hang Time Episode Guide|accessdate=October 3, 2010|work=[[TVrage]]}}</ref> Only other sources are imdb.com and http://homepage.mac.com/ijball/TEXT_guides/HTime-guide.txt--> After his championship 18th season in the NBA, Howard worked with [[Rick Ross]] to produce a [[rap music|rap]] song entitled "It's Time to Ball" from an album Howard was working on entitled ''Full Court Press Volume 1''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/blog/eye-on-basketball/19998608/heat-f-juwan-howard-records-rap-song-with-rick-ross-plans-to-release-album|title=Heat F Juwan Howard records rap song with Rick Ross, plans to release album|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=August 31, 2012|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Golliver, Ben}}</ref>

